<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Announces Sanctions Against Russian Institutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States imposed
economic sanctions Tuesday against a Moscow university and two
other Russian institutions, accusing them of leaking nuclear and
missile technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were against Mendeleyev Chemical Technical
University in Moscow, the Scientific Research and Design Institute
of Power and Technology and the Moscow Aviation Institute.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton's national security adviser Sandy Berger
announced the sanctions in a speech at the annual Carnegie
International Non-proliferation Conference.
</P>
<P>
"We've made it very clear the administration has authority to
act against entities that violate international nonproliferation
standards and we will use that authority to protect our security,"
Berger said.
</P>
<P>
The United States imposed similar sanctions against seven other
Russian institutions in July.
</P>
<P>
"Weapons scientists and institutions face increased financial
pressure to sell their wares to whomever is in the market,
including rogue states," Berger said.
</P>
<P>
Berger did not give details of the sanctions, acknowledging
that nonproliferation of Russian nuclear and missile technology
would not be stopped by U.S. penalties but requires a tighter
Russian export control system.
</P>
<P>
"Only Russia can police its own borders, factories and
technology industry," Berger said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Berger also pledged an all-out effort to gain
Senate ratification of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
Berger said it was critical to efforts to get India and
Pakistan to back away from nuclear testing. The treaty, signed by
151 nations, would ban all nuclear test explosions.
</P>
<P>
"It would be a terrible tragedy if the Senate failed to ratify
the CTBT this year," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
