<HEADLINE> Quorum Reached for Arab Foreign Ministers' Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A total of 17 countries have
agreed to attend an Arab consultation meeting of foreign
ministers, reaching the quorum for the session, the Arab League
sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Algeria and the United Arab Emirates separately informed the
league in the day of their decisions to take part in the meeting,
bringing the number to 17 of the countries agreeing to be present,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain and Saudi Arabia have verbally agreed to participate in
the meeting slated for January 24, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
In the 22 member states of the pan-Arab organization, Iraq,
Libya and Morocco have not made it clear whether they will be
represented.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries initially decided to hold the foreign ministers
meeting on December 30 to discuss the situation in Iraq following
a U.S.-British attack and a Yemeni call for an Arab summit on
restoring Arab solidarity.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and other Gulf
countries, the meeting was put off to January 24 for better
preparations and consultations.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain launched a four-day missile
attack on Iraq in mid-December in what the U.S. said a retaliation
for Iraq's defiance of the United Nations weapons inspections.
</P>
</TEXT>
