<HEADLINE> Balkan Defense Ministers Call for Peaceful Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Defense Ministers from Italy and
the southern Balkan countries Tuesday called for a peaceful
solution to the problem in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo through
negotiations between the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
Defense Ministers of Greece, Albania, Bulgaria, Italy, the
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM), Slovenia, the Chief
of Staff of Romania and ambassadors for the U.S. and Turkey are
now gathering in Athens to discuss the final details of the Balkan
multinational peacekeeping force, which was agreed last September
in Skopje, FYROM.
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos said that the
international community should now exert pressure upon the parties
concerned in Kosovo, aiming at finding a political solution which
allows granting autonomy to the ethnic Albanians within the
framework of the present borders of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Defense Minister Georgi Ananiev expressed the hope
that the Kosovo crisis would soon be resolved so that the force
would not have to be used.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Defense Minister Luan Hajdaraga said that the Kosovo
problem was "a problem of the entire Balkan region," since if it
spreads, it would inevitably affect all the countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed for any political solution to be based on
respect for the principles of self-determination and the
inviolability of present borders.
</P>
<P>
Italian Defense Minister Carlo Scognamiglio said that his
country had taken the decision to participate in both the
southeast Europe force and the NATO multinational force in FYROM
which will provide assistance to the observers of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in Kosovo if the
need arises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
