<HEADLINE> Russia, France Share View Over Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov and his visiting French counterpart Hubert Vedrine Tuesday
shared the same view that the role of the Contact Group in
settling the Kosovo problem should be increased, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said during a news conference after their talks that
"the Contact Group's role must be intensified."
</P>
<P>
He said the current pause in the settlement process is being
manipulated by forces that would like to further increase tensio
ns in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the recent seizure of eight Yugoslav officers by
Kosovo Albanians, he said if active political efforts are not
made such incidents will repeat themselves.
</P>
<P>
"The contact Group must send a strong signal to all sides
involved in the Kosovo conflict. They must sit at a negotiating
table and start discussing settlement problems," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
Echoing Ivanov, Vedrine said the United States' shuttle
diplomacy is not bringing results.
</P>
<P>
"We think the Contact Group must recapture the initiative and
assume responsibility for what has to do with the two conflicting
parties in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
On the Iraq problem, Ivanov said he supports working out "new
approaches" -- a reliable system -- to prevent Iraq from
producing weapons of mass destruction and to ensure conditions
for abolishing the oil embargo and thus alleviating the problems
of Iraq's people.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said as far as Iraq is concerned Russia and France
have very close positions, similar purposes and
mutually-supplementing approaches.
</P>
<P>
It is time the U.N. Security Council changed methods and forms
of its monitoring work in Iraq, Vedrine said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that at least the composition of the U.N. weapons
commission should be changed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
