<HEADLINE> Official: U.S.-DPRK Talks Go Ahead Despite Accusation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Talks between the United
States and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) will
go forward this week despite Pyongyang's accusation of U.S.
failure to faithfully implement a 1994 agreement on nuclear
reactors, a U.S. official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The talks will go forward. We are confident of that," the
official said. He was referring to the U.S.-DPRK talks in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
DPRK's newspaper, Rodong Sinmun, accused the United States in
an editorial on Tuesday of failing to keep its commitment of the
1994 Agreed Framework, under which Pyongyang abandoned its own
nuclear program in exchange for free fuel and commercial nuclear
power reactors.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has not faithfully implemented any of its
commitments... This compels the DPRK to expect nothing any longer
from the Agreed Framework," said the editorial, carried by the
Korean Central News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"We have no intention of observing the Geneva agreement because
the United States refuses to abandon its attempts to use it as a
lever to stifle the DPRK," the editorial added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official declined to comment on the editorial but said
the bilateral talks offered benefits to both sides.
</P>
<P>
The official said U.S. and DPRK officials will meet this
weekend. Next Tuesday, officials from China, the United States,
DPRK and South Korea will hold another round of four-party talks
on the future of the Korean Peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
