<HEADLINE> French PM Says Dollar Should Remain Reference Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin said on Tuesday that the U.S. dollar should remain the
world's reference money.
</P>
<P>
Jospin made the statement during a New Year good wish meeting
with the press.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the dollar would not remain the world's reference
money with the arrival of the euro, Jospin said, "It would not be
desirable that that change."
</P>
<P>
As for the proposal by Japan that the yen become another
international money beside the dollar and the euro, Jospin said t
hat it is still a question of whether the Japanese authorities
would make the yen an international money.
</P>
<P>
"It is not enough to proclaim," he said, in reference to the
statement made by Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi during his
visit to France last week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French Minister of Finance and Economy Dominique
Strauss-Kahn said on Tuesday that the euro does not intend to
replace the dollar.
</P>
<P>
He said it is natural for the euro to stay side-by-side with
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Some European economists have complained that the rate of the
euro could be too high for the economic growth of Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
