<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Still See Trade Surplus With Rest of World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The euro zone had a trade
surplus with the rest of the world of 5.2 billion euros in
September 1998, the European Union (EU) statistical office, the
Eurostat, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This figure gave the euro zone a total surplus of 63.9 billion
euros for the first nine months of 1998, up 0.8 billion euros
compared to the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Since the euro conversion rate with original European Currency
Unit, or ECU, is one to one, the two terms can be used
interchangeably for practical purpose, according to the Eurostat.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 11 of the 15 EU member states are in the euro zone.
They are Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Ireland, Italy,
Luxembourg, The Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland.
Britain, Sweden, Denmark and Greece are still outside the euro
zone.
</P>
<P>
However, extra-EU trade was one billion euros in deficit in
September 1998. And there was a surplus of only 14.3 billion
euros in the first nine months in 1998 compared to 32.5 billion
euros for the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, extra- and intra-trade growth in September was weak
or falling for both the euro zone and the EU. But EU trade with
the United States was well up in the first nine months last year,
with exports and imports increasing 15 percent and 13 percent,
respectively, from the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, effects of the situation in Asian financial
markets can be seen in a 14 percent fall in exports to Japan, and
the replacement of Taiwan by Hungary in the list of main trading
partners.
</P>
<P>
However, EU trade with China remains strong with an increase
of 15 percent for exports and 14 percent for imports, the
Eurostat data shows.
</P>
<P>
During the nine month period, Germany still enjoyed the
largest surplus with 51.7 billion euros, while Britain's deficit
rose strongly to 31.2 billion euros, and Ireland continued to
show the strongest growth with the third highest surplus of 14
billion euros. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
