<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supplementary Protocol on Balkan Multinational Force Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Defense ministers from Italy
and the southern Balkan countries signed here Tuesday a
supplementary protocol to the last September treaty to set up a
multinational peacekeeping force in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
According to the protocol, the multinational force's
headquarters will alternate every four years among the
participating countries in the order of Bulgaria,
Romania,Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
The command will be assigned to each of the countries for a
two-year term and Turkey will be the first followed by Greece.
</P>
<P>
The presidency and headquarters of the political and military
committee will be held by each of the participating countries for
a two-year term and Greece will hold the first presidency,
followed by Romania.
</P>
<P>
The multinational force's headquarters is expected to start
operating this summer while the participating countries hope to
hold the first exercise at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Slovenia and the United States are participating in the force
as observers.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will be ratified by the participating countries
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Defense Ministers from Greece, Albania, Bulgaria, Italy,
Macedonia, Slovenia, the Chief of Staff of Romania and
ambassadors of the United States and Turkey are present at the
meeting, which began here Monday to discuss a number of issues
concerning the force of between 3,000 and 4,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
The pact creating a multinational force was signed last
September at a meeting in the Macedonian capital, Skopje, but
disputes over where it should be based and who should head it
delayed its formal adoption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
