<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplane Fires Missile at Iraqi Radar Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. F-16 fighter fired a
HARM missile at a radar site in the northern no-fly zone in Iraq
on Tuesday, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. aircraft returned safely to its base in Incirlik,
Turkey. the clash took place at 11 a.m. Iraqi time (0800 GMT),
according to Pentagon spokesman Col. Richard Bridges.
</P>
<P>
It wasn't immediately clear why the pilot fired a missile at
the radar site, but Bridges said the "radar posed a threat to
coalition forces."
</P>
<P>
He said there was no further information, but it is possible
the radar had taken aim at the aircraft, as has occurred in
several previous incidents over the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
It was the second such military clash this week. On Monday U.S.
fighters attacked two Iraqi air defense missile sites in the
northern no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen, on a trip to Japan,
expressed the U.S. tough position after he was briefed of the
new clash, saying Baghdad would pay a price if it challenged
U.S. and British air might over the northern and southern no-fly
zones in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Cohen declined to say whether the repeated confrontations in
recent three weeks might prompt wider attacks against the Iraqi
military by American forces.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to protect our forces and take whatever measures
are necessary. Beyond that I woulddn't want to say anything," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The White House was also firm in its response to Iraq's
challenges in both no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
"The no-fly zones are being enforced vigorously and American
pilots will take the appropriate actions to respond to any action
taken against them," White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told
reporters on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two no-fly zones in northern and souther Iraq were set up
after the 1991 Gulf War. Iraq has announced it would no longer
recognize them since U.S.-British bombing raids against Iraqi
military and security targets in December.
</P>
<P>
Confrontations between the United States and Iraqi have thus
increased. And the main Arab nations -- Saudi Arabia and Egypt --
were infuriated by Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's call on Arabs
to overthrow their rulers, which made Iraq in a further isolated
position.
</P>
<P>
"It's been our experience that in times when he (Saddam
Hussein) is isolated and frustrated, he tries to lash out, and
we think now he is in a position where he has never been so
isolated and never been so frustrated," Lockhart said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Hopes New Turkish Government to Achieve Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Greece hoped the new Turkish
government-led by Bulent Ecevit to achieve political stability and
normality, government spokesman Yiannis Nikolaou said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Veteran politician Ecevit, 73, became the neighboring country's
new Prime Minister Monday after a six-week political crisis in
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Nikolaou said that the political
stability in Turkey would help Ankara in its European vocation and
in becoming a credible interlocutor.
</P>
<P>
Athens' desire was that any Turkish government respect
international treaties and contribute to conditions of good
neighborliness and peace in the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two NATO members have been strained for
decades over their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits, the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, both Greece and Turkey have made efforts to
improve their bilateral relations, but little progress has been
made so far due to their uncompromising stances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
