<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts to Resolve Cyprus Issue Intensify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. resident representative
Ann Hercus will leave Cyprus Wednesday evening for New York to
meet with United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the
Cyprus issue, Cyprus New Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hercus will stop over in London to hold talks with British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook. She will return to Cyprus on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the U.N. peacekeeping forces in
Cyprus said both meetings will focus on the U.N.'s 1999 agenda of
efforts to resolve the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Hercus restarted her shuttle talks in Nicosia after the
Christmas holiday with a meeting with Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday morning, Hercus will meet in the northern part of the
island Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, who was seeking
international recognition for an independent Turkish Cypriot
republic in norther Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The shuttle talks began in mid-October 1998 in a bid to revive
efforts for a solution to the protracted Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Clerides met with British High Commissioner David Madden on
Tuesday and the United States Ambassador to Cyprus Kenneth Brill
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Denktash met with Madded on Monday and he is scheduled to meet
with Brill on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup. The U.N. has been trying for
decades to reunite the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
