<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Most Greeks Dissatisfied With Public Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Most Greeks are dissatisfied
with public health services, according to the result of a survey
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted in 59 hospitals from June to December
last year by the Union of Consumers for Quality of Life (EKPOIZO),
aiming at evaluating the general level of service offered by
hospitals, and particularly how the institutions communicated with
those in need and extended information about services offered.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that more than 60 percent of those
interviewed said that communication with hospital personnel was
"moderate to bad," while more than 75 percent said that there was
no information about services within the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent said that the level of cleanliness left a lot to
be desired, 95 percent of hospitals surveyed lacked toilet paper
or soap in its facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
