<HEADLINE> Key Member of Israel's Labor Party Defects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A key member of the Israeli
Labor Party left the party Tuesday and decided to join in former
army chief of general staff to run in the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
Haggal Meron, also a member of the Knesset (parliament), was
the first leading Labor figure that left the party so far.
</P>
<P>
The centrist party formed by Amnon Lipkon-Shahak is the only
party that can beat the Likud led by Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in the May elections, Meron said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The Labor party is no longer my political home and I decided
to join Shahak," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shahak officially announced his candidacy for the premiership
last Thursday, attacking Netanyahu as "dangerous to Israel."
</P>
<P>
However, the Labor said Tuesday that Meron's quit will not
undermine the party's strength in its election campaign and it
does not bother the party at all.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said Tuesday that
he has not yet decided his political future and it still remains
uncertain whether he will stay or leave the Likud.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai told the Israel Radio that he would make a decision
"based on the interests of Israel, not on the interests of
Netanyahu."
</P>
<P>
Benny Begin and Dan Meridor, two key Likud members, have
already announced to compete in the elections.
</P>
<P>
After more than six years out of the political limelight,
Moshe Arens, former Likud defense minister and foreign minister,
announced on Monday to run against Netanyahu for the Likud
leadership.
</P>
<P>
Likud is to choose its candidate for the prime minister on
January 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
