<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Defense Minister
Moven Mahachi Tuesday said the Standard weekly newspaper will be
punished for publishing a false story of an attempted coup in the
Zimbabwe National Army (ZNA).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Harare, Mahachi said
military coups were taboo in the ZNA and the report was aimed at
tarnishing the image of the Zimbabwe Defense Forces (ZFD).
</P>
<P>
The privately-owned newspaper claimed last week that there was
a military coup in the ZNA and 23 army officers were arrested, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"These unscrupulous media are corrupt liars, and greedy to make
money at all costs, in a mercenary type media and damn cruel
intending to destroy by pen," Mahachi was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said while the government fully recognized the
freedom of the press as enshrined in the Constitution of Zimbabwe,
it also had the responsibility to protect the nation from
malicious misinformation deliberately intended to create
instability by some newspapers because of their financial greed.
</P>
<P>
"The government may be forced to take necessary steps to
protect the public, the people, armed forces and the right to be
told the truth," he
said. 
</P>
