<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriots' "Government" Wins Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A new "coalition government" of
the Turkish Cypriots in the northern part of Cyprus on Tuesday
secured a vote of confidence at its Assembly, Cyprus News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The government of the self-declared Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus," led by Dervis Eroglou as the premier, was
approved by a vote of 31-18.
</P>
<P>
Mustafa Akinci, leader of the Communal Liberation Party (TKP)
was named as deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial portfolios were shared by seven ministers from
the National Unity Party (UBP) and two from the TKP.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 the Turkish
Republic on the northern third of the east Mediterranean island,
which was recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern part in 1974
following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island, but
peace talks between the two sides have been stalled since 1997.
</P>
