<HEADLINE> Peres Forms New Israeli-Palestinian Youth Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Former Israeli prime minister
Shimon Peres announced in Tel Aviv Tuesday the formation of a new
Israeli-Palestinian Youth Council for peace, the Peres Peace
Center said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The council was founded with the aim of preparing the new
generations for peace, Peres said at the closing session of the
three-day meeting of the board of governors hosted by the center.
</P>
<P>
He said the council will bring together Israeli and Palestinian
youths regularly to conduct dialogs on what a peaceful future
they will build.
</P>
<P>
"The aim is to prepare new generations for peace because they
have the right and duty to create their future," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reviewed the operations of the center in 1998 and
worked out plans for 1999.
</P>
<P>
Participants visited the West Bank city of Ramallah on Monday
and discussed ways of moving the peace process forward with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Palestinian lawmakers there.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Palestinian Council (PC) there, Peres said the
1993 Oslo Accord between Israel and the Palestinians has laid down
the framework of Mideast peace process and the accord must be
fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
Among the participants were former Soviet Union president
Mikhail Gorbachev, South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu, former
United States Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and Polish
President Aleksander Kwasniewski, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa.
</P>
<P>
The center, set up by Peres last year, was aimed at enhancing
peace in the region through economic development and cooperation
in the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Peres said last week that the center has raised about 60
million U.S. dollars in 1998 and the money has to be well used in
promoting peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Besides helping the Palestinians enhance their educational,
agricultural and technical development, the center also plans
for the near future to form a Jordanian-Israeli fund to help
the Jordanians to speed up their economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
