<HEADLINE> Kuwait Agrees to U.S. Warplanes Reinforcement: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has agreed to the
deployment of eight more U.S. F-16 jet fighters in the Gulf to
defend the oil-rich emirate, Deputy Prime Minister and Defense
Minister Salem Sabah Al-Salem Al-Sabah said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed to the deployment of these aircraft in line
with the policy to beef up the defense of Kuwait," Salem told
reporters after a parliament session.
</P>
<P>
A United States military spokesman confirmed in Washington
earlier Tuesday that eight F-16 fighters would be sent in to
reinforce supervision of the no-fly zone in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 U.S. warplanes, along with more than 20 U.S. warships
and over 20,000 troops, are presently stationed in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Salem confirmed that part of the country's armed forces have
been put on high alert after Iraq stepped up war of words against
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"The Kuwaiti army is highly prepared to defend the national
territories," Salem said.
</P>
<P>
He declined to comment on reports that Iraq was massing up
troops near the Kuwaiti border and Iraq's implicit intention to
violate the no-fly zone in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi and U.S. warplanes have recently skirmished over the two
no-fly zones in southern and northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi officials said the no-fly zones, set up by the U.S. and
its western allies after the 1991 Gulf War, are illegal and they
threatened to shot down any foreign airplanes in its airspace.
</P>
</TEXT>
