<HEADLINE> NATO Inspectors Start Work in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A group of NATO experts Tuesday
started working in Southern Russia to monitor the implementation
of the Vienna document on measures for confidence-building and
security in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency quoted the Russian Defense Ministry
as saying that from january 12 to 14, the NATO group made up of
four British specialists will evaluate the information, supplied
by Russia, on the personnel, the main types of weapons and
military hardware of some army units, deployed in the Volgograd
Region.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, another NATO group consisting of Swedish
military inspectors as well launched out into monitoring the
fulfilment of the Vienna document in Kaliningrad.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish experts will work from January 12 to 15 on
appraising information of the Russian side on the personnel and
the main systems of armaments and military equipment in a number
of units in the Kaliningrad special district.
</P>
<P>
The Vienna document signed in 1994 combines new
confidence-building and security measures with the earlier adopted
measures registered in the 1986 document of the Stockholm
Conference.
</P>
<P>
The zone, where the confidence-building measures should be
taken, covers all the European countries participating in the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), as
well as the adjacent seas and air space. 
</P>
