<HEADLINE> Britain Supports U.N. Efforts on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- British High Commissioner in
Cyprus David Madden on Tuesday expressed Britain's full support to
the U.N. for a settlement of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides, Madden
said that Britain will continue to work closely with the
international community and in particular with the U.N. for a
settlement of the issue based on relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting between British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook and U.N. resident representative Dame Ann Hercus on Thursday
in London would be an initial step in Britain's efforts to support
the initiative the U.N. envoy proposed for a settlement of the
Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Noting that British Prime Minister Tony Blair had supported the
U.N. resolution 1218 in a written statement, Madden said that the
resolution is "particularly significant and important because it
sets out very clear objectives for future work and it sets out
some of the steps we would like to see taken."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed pro-Athens coup by Greek Cypriots. The Turkish Cypriots
unilaterally declared a republic in northern Cyprus in 1983, which
is only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-zonal, bi-communal federation formula.
</P>
<P>
The shuttle talks sponsored by Hercus began in mid-October
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
