<HEADLINE> Romania to Take Active Steps for Fighting Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Romanian government is to
take active steps for fighting unemployment, in view of the
redundancy due to massive shut-down of loss-making companies in
this year.
</P>
<P>
The effects of the Government's policy in this field will be
noticed by the end of 1999, the national Rompres news agency
Tuesday quoted Norica Nicolai, Secretary of State in the Ministry
of Labour and Social Security as saying.
</P>
<P>
The newly established National Agency for Employment and
Professional Training is ready to cover all governmental
programs of professional reconversion that will be implemented
for the first time by some private units at the Romanian
Government expense, he added.
</P>
<P>
Romania's unemployment rate is about 9 percent at present,
being estimated a possible rise as against the number of people
that will be made redundant due to the economic measures of the
government in 1999.
</P>
<P>
In order to create new jobs, the state grants credits for the
establishment of small and middle size enterprises. Ten thousands
of new jobs have been created in 1998 with an investment of 25-30
million lei (about 3000 U.S. dollars) for each one. The
expenditures made by the Romanian state for new jobs in 1998
totaled 4.2 million dollars plus unemployment expenditures.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Ministry of Labour and Social Security
found about 45,376 vacancies in Romania and 31,378 people were
hired out of 75,688 who were looking for jobs.
</P>
<P>
In view of the 1999 redundancy, Romania's Government will
continue the 1998 active steps with emphasis on those preceding
the lay-off. Among the active steps for fighting unemployment,
the Romanian state will stimulate economic units that hire fresh
university graduates on an open-ended labour contract. Norica
Nicolai also said that Romania's Government took into account some
steps that would fight "the black market of jobs". 
</P>
</TEXT>
