<HEADLINE> WFP Calls for Ceasefire Extension in Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- With only three days left
before a cease- fire agreement in southern Sudan expires, the head
of the U.N. World Food Program (WFP) warned Tuesday that a
continued cessation of hostilities was a must to avoid a repeat of
1998's famine, according to a release from the WFP Nairobi office
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"An escalation in fighting in southern Sudan will strike a
deadly blow to thousands of extremely fragile people there," said
Catherine Bertini, WFP Executive Director.
</P>
<P>
Bertini stressed : "So much help has been provided, and so many
lives have been saved, we simply cannot accept that a resurgence
in fighting wipes it all away."
</P>
<P>
The latest ceasefire agreement was renewed by the Sudanese
government and the Sudan People's Liberation Movement Army for
three months in mid-October 1998.
</P>
<P>
Last January, major clashes in Bahr El Ghazal Province in Sudan
forced hundreds of thousands of people to flee their homes to the
villages where the population was already weak. This sparked off
what evolved into one of the worst famines of this decade, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
Through this year, more than two million people in southern
Sudan will continue to require relief food in order to survive and
one-third of the hungry are in Bahr El Ghazal Province.
</P>
<P>
The release said that WFP, which launched the largest
humanitarian food airdrop in history, continues to deliver
thousands of tons of food each month to the victims of famine,
flooding and fighting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
