<HEADLINE> Security Council Condemns Downing of Two UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations on Tuesday adopted a resolution, condemning the
downing of two U.N. aircraft in Angola during the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
In the resolution, the Security Council deplored the loss
under suspicious circumstances of other commercial aircraft and
demanded that all such attacks cease immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Council reaffirmed its resolve to establish the truth
about the circumstances of and to determine the responsibility
for the downing of the two aircraft through an immediate and
objective international investigation.
</P>
<P>
The Council reiterated the demands that the leader of the
National Union for the Total Independence for Angola (UNITA), Jonas
Savimbi, comply with Council resolutions and cooperate
immediately and in good faith in the search for and rescue of
possible survivors of the incidents.
</P>
<P>
The Council welcomed the concrete actions undertaken by the
Government of Angola to follow up the commitment made by the
President of Angola to the Special Envoy of the U.N.
Secretary-General on January 5, 1999, regarding the cooperation
to be extended to the United Nations search and rescue efforts,
and encouraged it to continue to extend such cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Council requested the International Civil Aviation
Organization to provide all possible support to the
investigation of those incidents as soon as conditions on the
ground permit.
</P>
<P>
It stressed the obligation of member states to comply with the
measures imposed against UNITA under its relevant resolutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
