<HEADLINE> Drug Abuse Rise 20-Fold in 10 Years in Moldova </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Drug addiction rose 20-fold
in the Republic of Moldova over the last 10 years and local
experts estimated that the number of abusers are between 40,000
and 120,000.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the Interior Ministry, quoted Tuesday
by the local BASA-Press news agency, of the total 3,969 drug
dependents officially registered, 252 are children, and some 2,450
are young people of 20-25 years old.
</P>
<P>
The spread of drug abuse contributes to the rise of the crime
in general, the report read. In the last five years, the number of
drug related crimes has risen three times. In 1998 alone, police
discovered 870 drug related crimes and offenses, which is 8.5
percent up compared to 1997.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show some 25-30 tons of poppy are in illegal trade
in Moldova. A glass of poppy straws is sold 30 lei (about 3 U.S.
dollars) on the black market.
</P>
<P>
"The lack of desire in society to take measures and continuous
spread of the drug trade will lead to considerable increase of the
number of drug related crimes," said police colonel Andrei
Vataman, chief of the Interior Ministry's anti-drug service.
According to him, it is necessary "to intensify criminal
persecution against the drug traffickers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
