<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Egypt warned Tuesday of
instability in the Middle East if Israel fails to carry out the
peace agreements signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"The failure to enforce these accords implies danger to the
regional scene in general and the peace process in particular,"
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Moussa called on the Israeli government to reconsider its
policy and implement the accords as part of the efforts to salvage
the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has recently
suspended the U.S.-brokered Wye accord for alleged Palestinian
non-compliance.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord signed by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Netanyahu last October in Washington, Israel should withdraw from
another 13 percent of the West Bank in three phases by the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said his brief visit to Israel on Monday is "very
useful," adding that it is necessary to have "direct and frank
dialog" with Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of a gathering of the peace center named after
former Israeli prime minister Shimon Peres, Moussa met with
Israeli President Ezer Weizman, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon,
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and leader of the opposition
Labor Party Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian official maintained that his visit and meetings
provided the opportunity to highlight the importance of carrying
out the agreements signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Moussa stressed that without the creation of a Palestinian
state, stability in the region would be jeopardized and the peace
process would be "in an illogical position and become
counter-productive."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have announced to declare an independent state
in May according to the Oslo accords signed with Israel in 1993.
Netanyahu has opposed the step, threatening to take unilateral
actions against the possible move. 
</P>
