<HEADLINE> Tanzanian PM Urges People to Sell Cattle for Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye Tuesday urged people in famine-stricken areas to
sell cattle and take all possible means to cushion the effects of
food shortages.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to villagers in Nzuguni Ward of Dodoma Urban District
in central Tanzania, Sumaye said that the government cannot allow
some cattle owners to have large herds for prestige while their
families are starving.
</P>
<P>
"You must sell your cattle so that you can feed your families,
send your children to school and pay your medical expenses," he
directed.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, Sumaye said it is a bad
habit for people to always bank on donations when they have no
food.
</P>
<P>
He criticized pastoralists in the northern Arusha Region who
ignored his call to sell their cattle to buy food, even when a bag
of maize is selling at 20,000 Shillings (about 30 U.S. Dollars)
compared with 3,000 Shillings previously.
</P>
<P>
Most of the regions in Tanzania have suffered from grave
shortages due to bad weather last year. The government has
appealed for urgent food relief as 600,000 tons of food are wanted
in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The premier said the weather departments have predicted that
the country will have inadequate rains this year, a situation
which requires people to tighten their belts.
</P>
<P>
He also called on farmers to plant drought resistant crops and
businessmen to boost food circulation.
</P>
<P>
Officiating the 35th anniversary celebrations for Zanzibar
Revolution at Uhuru Primary School in Dodoma later, Sumaye said it
is a shame for a nation to beg for food.
</P>
<P>
He said while celebrating the isle's revolution which toppled
Arab Sultanese regime, Tanzanians should initiate another
revolution to fight hunger.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye urged Tanzanians to change their attitudes toward work
and make greater efforts to combat poverty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
