<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa's Y2K Program on Track: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Y2K
readiness program is on track and it is expected that by the end
of this year the country will be 65-70 percent compliant, said Jay
Naidoo, Minister of Posts and Communications.
</P>
<P>
"This (percentage) is a conservative figure and assumes that
all the sectors will at least maintain their current rate of
progress.
</P>
<P>
"The country's level of readiness is very dependent on the
extent to which all key players participate in the Y2K challenge,"
Naidoo was quoted as saying by a government statement issued
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He assured the public there is no need for panic, though there
is a need for concerted action by companies, and a need to educate
the general public.
</P>
<P>
He added that mission critical systems -- those in control of
essential services -- will be close to full compliance by the end
of this year, meaning that the majority of people will experience
only minor disruptions in essential services.
</P>
<P>
Most major organizations are progressing well with their
individual Y2K programs, Naidoo said.
</P>
<P>
However, many organizations have not paid due attention to the
inter- connected nature of their businesses and had ignored their
dependence on other organizations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem, also called the millennium bug, stems from the
fact that old computers recognizes a year only by the last digits.
When the clock of the computer ticks to the year 2000, the
computer will take it as the year 1900, thus causing confusion in
all calculations and operations which take a date into account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
