<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Rate in France in December Lowest since 1953 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The consumer prices in France in
December 1998 rose by 0.3 percent as compared with the same month
in 1997, scoring the lowest year-on-year inflation rate since
December 1953.
</P>
<P>
The official economic statistics bureau INSEE said on Tuesday
that prices rose by 0.1 percent in December over November.
</P>
<P>
In December 1953, consumer prices fell by 2.3 percent in
France.
</P>
<P>
The INSEE said that low inflation rate does not mean that
France is experiencing deflation, as the economy is still growing
and jobs are created.
</P>
<P>
However, excluding government fixed prices such as public
transport and seasonal prices such as fresh foods and energy, the
inflation rate in France would attain 1.1 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
Food prices rose only by 0.5 percent in December as compared
with 2.5 percent in the same month 1997, while energy prices fell
by 5.2 percent as compared with a fall of 0.3 percent in the same
month 1997.
</P>
<P>
The falling oil price in the world market was one major factor
contributing to low inflation in France.
</P>
<P>
The INSEE said that if world oil price can stabilize in
mid-1999, inflation rate could rise to around 0.5 percent in June
as compared with June 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
