<HEADLINE> Germany, Japan Want More Cooperation in World Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany and Japan want more
transparency in international financial transactions, agreed
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi and German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder in their talks in Bonn Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This issue would be on the agenda at a meeting of European
Union and Asian finance ministers in Frankfurt this Friday and at
the June G-8 summit of leaders from wealthy industrial nations and
Russia in Cologne, said Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder also said Bonn and Tokyo would cooperate in efforts
to stabilize the economic situation in Russia, but did not give
details.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi tried to declare that the yen was fit to remain a world
currency with the dollar and the euro. He said the yen's strength
depended on the strength of the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
"The euro has had a very nice start," said Obuchi. "I hope the
euro will be as strong as the dollar." The euro was launched by 11
EU states on January 1.
</P>
<P>
Both countries had agreed also to work together on reforming
the United Nations and strengthening the position of the U.N.
secretary-general, said Schroeder, who accepted an invitation to
visit Japan this autumn.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi wrapped up a three-nation Europe tour in Bonn from Italy
and France. He flew back to Japan late Tuesday after having a
dinner with Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Obuchi met German President Roman Herzog in Berlin
Monday and Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer in Bonn Tuesday.
</P>
