<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Unveils Plan to Preserve Sensitive Lands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
unveiled a plan Tuesday to triple spending in an effort to
preserve vulnerable lands in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Our population is growing, our cities are growing, our
commitment to conservation must grow as well," Clinton said in
announcing the 1 billion U.S. dollars spending proposal during a
ceremony at the National Arboretum.
</P>
<P>
The "land-legacy initiative" will be included in the fiscal
2000 budget Clinton will send to Congress next week.
</P>
<P>
It calls for adding thousands of acres to the system of
federally protected lands and providing states with nearly 600
million dollars for land preservation.
</P>
<P>
Among the protected areas that would be expanded under the plan
are the Joshua Tree National Park in California and the Florida
Everglades, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement comes a day after Vice President Al Gore
unveiled a separate program that proposes to use 700 million
dollars in tax credits to finance a 10 billion dollars bond
program aimed at creating suburban parks, greenways and other open
space.
</P>
<P>
That proposal was aimed at dealing with suburban sprawl, while
the new initiative is directed at restoring and protecting
undeveloped, but vulnerable, forests, grasslands, beaches and
marine sanctuaries, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Over three decades ago, Congress created a land and water
conservation fund that authorized spending as much as 900 million
dollars a year to buy land for conservation. But in most years
only about a third of that money was ever provided and during the
Reagan administration land purchases were put on hold.
</P>
<P>
This year, Congress provided about 320 million dollars for
federal land purchases.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton proposal calls for full funding of the program and
would funnel millions of dollars more -- for a total of just over
1 billion dollars a year -- into land preservation. Most of the
money would come from revenues collected from offshore oil
drilling, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
