<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Rebel Leader in Guinea for Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's detained rebel
leader Foday Sankoh was flown from his jail to neighboring Guinea
for talks with mediators Tuesday, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Sierra Leonean Ambassador to Guinea, Ali
Kamara, as saying in a telephone interview that Sankoh went
straight into talks with west African ministers, the United
Nations and the Sierra Leonean government.
</P>
<P>
"He is here in Conakry and is in negotiations," the ambassador
said.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh's transfer abroad is a key demand of his Revolutionary
United Front (RUF) fighters before they will consider a cease-fire
or political talks.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, who led the RUF rebellion in 1991, was put under house
arrest in Nigeria in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
He was handed over to the Sierra Leonean authority after the
west African peace-keeping force chased out the military junta of
Johnny Paul Koromah and restored the government of elected
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh was sentenced to death by a Sierra Leonean court last
October for calling on his supporters to ally with the Koromah
junta, though the execution has not been carried out to allow him
to appeal to the higher court.
</P>
<P>
Since Sankoh's death sentence was announced, the rebels have
intensified their attacks and eventually controlled the whole
northern half of Sierra Leone, before they entered the capital
Freetown last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the heat of the fighting between the Nigerian-led ECOMOG
and rebels, Sierra Leone's state radio announced that President
Kabbah and Sankoh had reached a cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
But the rebel's field commander and number two leader Sam
Bockarie said the cease-fire was not true and that his troops
would fight on until Sankoh was released.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leonean government has reportedly asked Guinea and
Cote d' Voire to mediate the peace talks, while the international
society, including Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) as well as the United Nations have been playing a
positive role in trying to find a solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ECOMOG forces Tuesday continued its mop-up
operations in Freetown, with the rebels retreating from the
central and eastern parts of the city they once occupied.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed ECOMOG officer said there were still small groups of
rebels and isolated gunmen and that it will take another few days
before the city is safe again.
</P>
<P>
The retreating rebels reportedly resorted to murder of
civilians, arson and looting, as witnesses said bodies littered
the streets and many houses were burnt down.
</P>
<P>
As the fighting rages on, thousands of residents remained
trapped in their houses without food, water or electricity.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Red Cross and the United
Nations High Commission for Refugees in Geneva have warned that a
humanitarian disaster is looming until some kind of ceasefire is
arranged and humanitarian supplies can be brought in.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
