<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China And Bigfoot (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Feng Zuojian says that if the creature really exists and has
been seen hundreds of times, why is it described in so many
different ways?
</P>
<P>
When the Shennongjia forest was examined several years ago,
scientists found that the environment of the mainly coniferous
forest had been destroyed somewhat, but that the essential living
condition for the creature, like broad-leaved trees and berries,
were not enough, according to Pan Wenshi, a life sciences
professor at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
However, Huang Wanbo, of the Chinese Academy of Sciences'
Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology, says
that although the creature may not exist today, perhaps it did
several hundred years ago.
</P>
<P>
Although its possible existence has largely been ignored by
mainstream scientists, several thousand people have claimed to
have encountered it and very large unexplained footprints have
indeed been found in forested parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Guoxing, of the Beijing Museum of Natural History, says
that there are still many mysteries in nature like Bigfoot and
UFOs that will still cause investigators to go and have a look.
</P>
<P>
But, Pan Wenshi cautions, protecting the environment rather
than looking for mythical creatures is a far more pressing task
in China now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Not Taking Part In Search For Bigfoot (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China will not support the
search for Bigfoot, the legendary large, hairy, man-like
creature, which has been reported for years in the forests of
Shennongjia in Hubei Province, according to a State Forestry
Administration official.
</P>
<P>
The official says the administration opposes the reward of
500,000 yuan (60,000 U.S. dollars) that is being offered by the
tourism department of Shennongjia to anyone who finds Bigfoot.
</P>
<P>
A number of Chinese scientists have ruled out any possibility
that the creature exist. Since the mid-1970s, Chinese scientists
have had several large-scale search for Bigfoot around
Shennongjia, but have failed to find any conclusive evidence of
the creature's existence, according to Feng Zuojian, of the C
hinese Academy of Sciences' Institute of Zoology.
</P>
<P>
Both a skull and a piece of the creature's hair are needed to
prove its existence. So far, only hair or excrement that tests
later proved to have come from other animals have been found,
says Chen Xiaoyi, of China Science Popularization Publishing
House.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the sightings of Bigfoot were reported in areas that
were not far from towns, and I hardly believe they exist so close
to human activities," Chen says.
</P>
<P>
The creature is said to average six and a half feet in height
and to have left large footprints of up to sixteen inches and to
be covered with thick brown or red or white hair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
