<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sports Minister Says Wembley Sale Boosts World Cup Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Tony Banks, British sports
minister, said on Wednesday that the sale of Wembley Stadium
could be a boost to England's bid for the the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Wembley Plc said earlier that it had agreed to sell the venue
for 103 million pounds (169 million U.S. dollars), ending months
of uncertainty and clearing the way for the development of a new
national stadium on the site.
</P>
<P>
The new stadium is central to England's 2006 bid and Banks
said until the sale was settled the bid was being held back.
</P>
<P>
"Now we know it is secure we can go into the last 12 months
(of the bidding period) on a high," said Banks.
</P>
<P>
"Now we are ready to move pretty fast. There is a great deal
of national pride and prestige behind it."
</P>
<P>
Banks said there were still a number of issues to be raised,
including the future of the stadium's famous twin towers which,
at the very least, will have to be moved, but said he was
delighted by the sale.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped the new stadium would be ready in time for th
e 2002 F.A. Cup final but said a more realistic target was the
following year, when the new stadium hopes to host the world
athletics championships.
</P>
<P>
On the 2006 World Cup bid, Banks said: "We have a very, very
strong case and we maintain we are the number one contender.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very tight contest but there are only 24 people to
persuade -- the members of FIFA (executive committee)."
</P>
<P>
Banks said he was annoyed with some sections of the media who
have not given full support to the bid.
</P>
<P>
"I would like people to realise this is a national effort
which has the full backing of (Prime Minister) Tony Blair and the
government," said Banks.
</P>
<P>
Seven other countries bidding for the 2006 World Cup are
Germany, Brazil, South Africa, Nigeria, Ghana, Egypt and M
orocco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
