<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Nuclear Weapons Cooperation With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi on Wednesday dismissed recent
allegations made by U.S. officials about weapons cooperation
between Iran and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Asefi condemned the statements "which violate Iran's natural
right to use nuclear energy for peaceful purposes," the Islamic
Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
U.N. National Security adviser Sandy Berger on Tuesday
announced economic sanctions on three Russian institutions for
"directly supporting Iran's efforts to develop nuclear weapons."
</P>
<P>
The sanction bans all exports to and imports from the Moscow
Aviation Institute, the Mendeleyev Chemical Technical University
and the Scientific Research and Design Institute of Power and
Technology, which were accused of failing to prevent leaks of
nuclear and missile technologies to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Berger stressed that continued contacts and commerce with Iran
on nuclear weapon and missile technology is a threat to the United
States, to Russia and to the world.
</P>
<P>
last July, the U.S. also imposed sanctions on seven Russian
institutes and factories on the same charges.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman said that Berger's statements were aimed
at diverting public attention from Washington's "unsparing
support" for Israel, which is "a potential threat to the region
for possessing all kinds of destructive weapons."
</P>
<P>
Asefi said that Iran's missile industries are completely
indigenous and that Iran does not rely on any country to this end.
</P>
<P>
Iran is not after stockpiling atomic weapons and its military
facilities play solely defensive roles, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Iranian embassy in Moscow on Wednesday also
denied the allegations that Iran was engaged in missile and
nuclear cooperation with the three Russian institutions.
</P>
<P>
The embassy said in a statement that the allegations were
repetition of the same old accusations already denied by both
Iranian and Russian officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
