<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Trade Deficit Down by 47 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's trade deficit
decreased by 47.4 percent during the first half of the 1998-99
fiscal year compared with that of the same period in the previous
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of the current fiscal year (July 1, 1998
to June 30, 1999), the country's trade deficit fell to 594 million
U.S. dollars from 1,130 million dollars in the same period of the
previous fiscal year, the Associated Press of Pakistan (APP)
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive strategy worked out by the government has led
to considerable improvement in the balance of trade despite the
staggering economic climate confronting the country in the wake of
economic sanctions, the report quoted official sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has set the target of bringing the
trade deficit down to a zero level through various pragmatic
measures including bringing down imports, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Total imports during the first six months (July-December) of
the 1998-99 fiscal year fell by 19.6 percent to 4,397 million
dollars from 5,472 million dollars during the same period of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the amount of total exports also showed a downward
trend, decreasing by 12.4 percent from the previous year's 4,342
million dollars to 3,803 million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Experts here are of the view that widespread economic recession
in Asia, sharp decline in the prices of products in the world
market and the economic sanctions imposed on Pakistan by the West
have resulted in the reduction in the country's imports and
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
