<HEADLINE> Unbeaten Bayi Rockets Runs Winning Streak to Six Matches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (xinhua) -- National player Liu Yudong
scored a game-high 26 points to lead defending chamion Bayi
Rockets to overpower hosts Jiangsu Dagons 126-92 in the sixth
round of the Chinese first division basketball league in Nanjing
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
 The Rockets, fourth time champion since Chinese basketball
introduced the professional league in 1995, remained unbeaten and
proved they enjoyed a comfortable advantage over the other 11
teams.
</P>
<P>
 The dragons, whoes twice regular season MVP Hu Weidong was
sidelined because of an injury, counted on Zhang Guodong and
American Gree Roberson to open an early lead 10-9 right after the
start.
</P>
<P>
 But the Rockets took command very soon thanks to national
star center Wang Zhizhi and finish the first half 59-47.
</P>
<P>
 The powerful Rockets never slowed down their pace in the
second half and swept to victory with ease.
</P>
<P>
 Roberson and Liu Guodong led the Dragons with 19 points
apiece.
</P>
<P>
 "Hu's absence dealt a heavy blow to us. We should have done
better if he had not been injured," said Li Changshan, head coach
of the Dragons.
</P>
<P>
 But Li admitted that the Rockets are much stronger than
them. "I have never expected to beat them. There's a big gap
between us."
</P>
<P>
 Liaoning Hunters took their fifth win in six games to remain
the second place in the team standings, beating Jilin Northeast
Tigers 135-112 on a home turf in Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
 But the hero of the match was Northeast Tiger's national
forward Sun Jun, who scored a game-high 40 points including a
round-high nine three-pointers.
</P>
<P>
 It was a see-saw game in the first half, which ended 59-55
in the Hunters' favor. But the Hunters stepped up offence in the
second and extended the lead to 99-76 after the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
 "We're too weak in rebounds. I think this is the most
important reason to explain our loss," said Zhang Xiaochun, head
coach of the Northeast Tigers.
</P>
<P>
 In the other matches, Hongyuan Guangdong Tigers beat Jinan
Army Pegasus 100-76, Zhejiang Cyclone routed Shanghai Sharks
115-108, Beijing Aoshen ousted Beijing Ducks 88-79, Shandong
Flaming Bulls defeated Sichuan Pandas 96-78. 
</P>
</TEXT>
