<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Lowest Inflation Since Reunification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Falling fuel and food prices
helped cut inflation in Germany to a post-reunification low of
just 0.9 per cent in 1998, half the 1.8 per cent rise recorded the
year before, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Statistics Office said there was no month-to-month
increase from November to December. In December itself, prices
were just 0.5 per cent higher than 12 months earlier. In November
the year-to-year rise was 0.7 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The average 1998 rate was the lowest since the office began to
compile combined data for eastern and western Germany in 1991, the
first full calendar year after reunification in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In 1987, then-West Germany had an inflation rate of just 0.2
per cent.
</P>
<P>
The office said last year's favorable price trends chiefly
were the result of dropping oil prices, a decline which more than
compensated for the one percentage point increase, to 16 per cent,
in the value-added tax last April.
</P>
<P>
On average, heating oil prices fell 24.6 per cent and fuel
prices by 7.4 per cent compared with 1997, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Besides more favorable oil and fuel prices, food costs were
also much cheaper during the course of 1998, the report showed.
Meat prices fell 2.1 per cent, fruit by 9.3 per cent and coffee by
3.2 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The office said that Germany's inflation outlook for 1999 would
remain favourable.
</P>
<P>
Raw materials prices were expected to remain depressed due to
lower demand resulting from the crises in Russia, Asia and Latin
America, while overcapacity in major industrial sectors around the
world, coupled with cost-cutting efforts by corporations, would
serve to keep prices in check.
</P>
<P>
The report follows predicts by the chief economists of the
three big Frankfurt-based banks, Deutsche, Dresdner and
Commerzbank, that German inflation this year would be between 0.9
and 1.3 per cent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
