<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 21 Suspected Terrorist Arrested in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 21 operatives for a
dozen of the world's most notorious terrorist groups have been
arrested in Canada in the past nine years, the National Post
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Those caught by Canadian authorities since 1991 include
members of the radical Islamic group Hezbollah, the anti-western
Mujahedin, a shadowy Middle Eastern commando group named Force
17, and Black September, part of the Libya-based Abu Nidal
organization.
</P>
<P>
the 21 operatives, all considered national-security risks,
were arrested under a federal anti-terrorism law, the newspaper
quoted Canadian immigration officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
14 have been deported and another six are still waiting to be
tried. One deportation attempt was rejected by the courts, added
the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
While the number of suspected terrorists picked up across the
country remains small, their affiliation to a range of
organizations responsible for some of the worst acts of violence
of the past two decades is a concern to those charged with
safeguarding the security of Canadians.
</P>
<P>
Terrorists are attracted to Canada for a variety of reasons,
officials said, ranging from using the country to raise funds for
arms purchases, to its easy access to the United States.
</P>
<P>
A rising concern is the growth of Islamic terrorism, officials
said, particularly since the call-to-arms issued in the wake of
the American and British bombing campaigns in Iraq, which
followed the break-down of United Nations weapons inspection
efforts established after the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
As part of its anti-terrorism efforts, Canada screens
thousands of visitors and applicants for immigration every year
to ensure they are not security risks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
