<HEADLINE> U.S. Sanctions against Russian Organizations Denounced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov Wednesday strongly criticized the U.S. for applying
sanctions against Russian organizations, saying "the use of force
or sanctions against our organizations are counter-productive in
Russian-U.S. relations, to which we attach great importance,"
said the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
The United States imposed economic sanctions Tuesday against
three Russian institutions and accused them of transferring
rocket and nuclear technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were directed against Mendeleyev Chemical
Technology University, the Research Institute of Energy
Technology and the Moscow Aviation Institute.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot comment on this information right now," Primakov
said. "I must study it in all its aspects, and study the
conditions of the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Russian Foreign Ministry noted in a
statement that the U.S. sanctions against the three Russian
institutes "may complicate Russian-American relations.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally, the latest moves by the United States will not go
unanswered," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said it intends to raise this issue at
the highest political level during Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright's upcoming visit to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Russian investigatory agencies revealed that the charges of
assisting Iran in implementing missile and nuclear programs,
brought against three Russian institutes, "Are unfounded,"
according to the document.
</P>
<P>
"the U.S. administration's moves are at odds with the
agreements on the development of bilateral cooperation on
non-proliferation and in export control, which were reached by
the Russian and American presidents in September 1998."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mendeleyev University Rector Pavel Sarkisov said
the U.S. decision to apply sanctions to three Russian
organizations was "absolutely groundless".
</P>
<P>
He said the Chemical Technology University "is not engaged in
any nuclear research and has no direct or covert agreements with
Iran."
</P>
<P>
"We have offered all the persons concerned, including
Americans, to visit our educational institutions and to draw
their own conclusions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
