<HEADLINE> U.S. Attacks Iraqi Radar Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. warplanes
patrolling the northern no-fly zone on Wednesday attacked Iraqis
radar sites, the third such incident this week, a Pentagon
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Air Force F-15 and F-16 jet fighters encountered Iraqi
radar at five or more air defense sites at about the same time.
They fired high-speed, anti-radiation missiles and AGM-130
precision-guided bombs in response, and early indications were
that two AGM-130s scored direct hits, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred at about 3 a.m.(0800GMT)
</P>
<P>
All the U.S. warplanes returned safely to their bases in Turkey
after attacking the Iraqi air defense radar sites near the city of
Mosul, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's attack was the seventh such incident in the past
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon spokesman said there also were two Iraqi
incursions into the no-fly zone over southern Iraq on Wednesday.
He said no U.S. planes were in the area at the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
