<HEADLINE> Russia, Kyrgyzstan Tighten Bilateral Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said on Wednesday that relations between Russia and
Kyrgyzstan have reached a new level.
</P>
<P>
After talking with his visiting Kyrgyzstan counterpart
Zhumabek Ibraimov, Primakov told reporters that the two countries
have begun the creation of joint ventures, expansion of bilateral
trade and the boosting of the customs union.
</P>
<P>
Primakov noted that it's an integration step which should be
taken by other member states of the Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS).
</P>
<P>
Ibraimov said talks in the framework of the Union will broaden
economic integration, particularly in industry.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the two leaders also signed agreements on
cooperation in information matters, avoiding double taxation and
the prevention of income tax evasion during their meeting.
</P>
<P>
An inter-departmental memorandum on ties between small
businesses was also signed.
</P>
<P>
Ibraimov arrived here for an official visit on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
