<HEADLINE> U.S. Attacks Iraqi Radar Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. warplanes patrolling
in the northern no-fly zone on Wednesday attacked Iraqi radar
sites, the third such incident this week, a Pentagon spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft returned safely to their bases in Turkey after
attacking the Iraqi early-warning radar sites near the city of
Mosul, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's attack was the seventh incident in the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Details of Wednesday's incident were sketchy but officials in
Washington and at the U.S. European Command in Stuttgart,
Germany, said the U.S. warplanes apparently scored direct hits on
at least two Iraqi air defense radar sites. They fired
anti-radiation missiles and precision-guided bombs, The incident
occurred at about 0800 GMT.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon spokesman said there were also two Iraqi
incursions into the no-fly zone over southern Iraq on Wednesday.
He said no U.S. planes were in the area at the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
