<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Fifth Peak Of Criminal Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China is now going through a
fifth peak of criminal activity, with crimes reported in the
mid-1990s running about 8 times what they were more than a decade
ago, according to Cao Feng, an associate professor at Chinese Peo
ple's University of Public Security.
</P>
<P>
Cao has told Procuratorial Daily that current criminal
activities include more serious cases like armed robberies at
financial institutions and jewelry shops.
</P>
<P>
Juvenile delinquency, abuse of power by officials, dru
g-related crimes, and pornography have all become problems in
China, Cao told the paper, and attributed their cause to a change
in systems and the social framework. Because society as a whole
is more vain and because the legal system is not complete, she s
ays, the number of law breakers is on the rise in China.
</P>
<P>
Cao suggests a more dynamic and comprehensive security network
for the family, society, and schools to stop criminal activities
during this peak period.
</P>
<P>
The first peak came after the founding of the People's
Republic of China in 1949, and was characterized by
counter-revolutionary activities and a survival of earlier
problems.
</P>
<P>
The second peak came in the 1960s when China had a series of
natural disasters that led to an increase in the number of cases
of theft of property.
</P>
<P>
China had a third and fourth peak of criminal activities
during the Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) and at the beginning
of the reform and opening-up period in 1978.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's LDP and LP Reach Agreement on Paving Way for Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Liberal Democratic Party
(LDP) and the Liberal Party (LP) on Wednesday struck an agreement
on key policy issues concerning security, and paving the way for
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi to reshuffle his cabinet to launch a
LDP-LP coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Japan's Self Defense Forces (SDF) will
"actively participate and cooperate" in U.N. peacekeeping
missions if they are authorized by U.N. resolutions and if Japan
is asked by the United Nations to contribute its forces, party
officials said.
</P>
<P>
But the SDF will not participate in battles and will not take
part in activities that are integrated in missions that involve
the use of force, such as the shipment of goods to battle zones,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The two parties also agreed that a decision on whether the SDF
can participate in certain missions will be made by the cabinet
on a case-by-case basis, they said.
</P>
<P>
Policies concerning the role the SDF can play in U.N. missions
differed between the two parties and had been a sticking point in
the two parties' negotiations for the formation of a coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
The two parties have been squabbling over policy differences
on defense since the coalition was first proposed last November.
</P>
<P>
On a set of bills for implementing the updated guidelines for
defense cooperation between Japan and the United States, the two
parties basically agreed to support the bills, but will continue
talks on some points in the bills, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Japan and the U.S. updated the 1979 defense
guidelines to strengthen cooperation between the two countries in
the event of emergencies in "areas surrounding Japan."
</P>
<P>
The package of bills, which was submitted by the government
last April, is expected to be deliberated in the coming regular
Diet (parliament) session, which convenes January 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Sign Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Singapore will sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) on January 14, 1999, the
Singapore Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MFA) announced in a press
statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
MFA said "Singapore's signature of the CTBT demonstrates its
commitment to the treaty's objectives, and to the efforts of the
international community in working towards a nuclear-weapon-free
world."
</P>
<P>
Opened for signature on September 24, 1996, the CTBT's
objective is to bring an end to nuclear weapons testing with the
ultimate goal of eliminating nuclear weapons, MFA said.
</P>
<P>
According to MFA, up to date 151 countries have signed the
treaty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
