<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Export Increase: Hard to Come By (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China's exports increased only
0.5 percent in 1998, but even that modest figure was hard won
with pressure from the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
China's imports and exports were down 0.4 percent from the
previous year, but exports overall were worth 183.76 billion U.S.
dollars, up 0.5 percent, according to Chinese Customs.
</P>
<P>
The year was unexpectedly hard on China's exporters. The
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC)
suggested export growth of 10 percent early in 1998 after
considering the Asian financial turmoil. But its negative effects
went far beyond what people expected. Export decreased almost
monthly after March, and fell continuously from August to
November. During that period, they were the lowest in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The countries of Southeast Asia and China's other neighbors,
where most of China's exports go, were hit hard by the financial
crisis and exports were down dramatically because of currency
devaluations.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Asia were worth 98.2 billion U.S. dollars in 1998,
down 9.9 percent from a year before. The slow-down in the global
economy lowered the price of raw materials and other products,
meaning less income from exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Export Increase: Hard to Come By (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese Government promptly made adjustments, lowering
bank interest rates several times last year to encourage exports
and cut operation costs.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC officials held several seminars for foreign trade
departments and trade companies and had a vigorous export
encouragement policy. It also asked trade officials and companies
to make a great effort up to the last minute of 1998 to reach the
target.
</P>
<P>
Some provincial governments came up with policies to encourage
local trade companies to increase exports.
</P>
<P>
Through this joint effort, exports brought things out of the
red in the last month of 1998. December's exports were worth 20
billion U.S. dollars, up 4.3 percent from the same month of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Exports to other parts of the world, especially the United
States and Europe, were also up a great deal. Exports to the
United States were worth 37.98 billion U.S. dollars, up 16.1
percent, and to the EU, 28.15 billion U.S. dollars, up 18.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
This growth in 1998 was not easy to come by, compared with
some Asian nations which scored a sharp decrease in exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0099 </DOCNO>
