<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Discipline Inspection Commission Holds Plenum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection of the Communist Party of China (CPC) held
its third plenary session in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The main topics for discussion were a review of improvements
in the Party's work, building a clean government and fighting
corruption in 1998, and objectives for the new year.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, secretary of the Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection, reported that progress had been made in
building cleaner government and opposing corruption, especially
in curbing extravagance and waste in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Party and government organizations at or above the county
level have found 569,000 unwarranted telephones at the homes of
Party and government officials and 383,000 mobile phones
purchased with public funds. A new management system for phones
is expected to help cut public expenditure by 2.5 billion yuan
annually, Wei said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of October, China had suspended construction work,
or expansion work and decoration on 11,000 office buildings,
canceled 22,000 celebration activities and called off overseas
visits by 7,400 groups.
</P>
<P>
Wei, a Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of
the CPC Central Committee, said that discipline inspection
departments had received reports of more than 1.61 million cases
of corruption by the end of November, investigated 142,000 cases,
and reached a decision on 124,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
Of Party members who were penalized, 3,970 were officials at
the county magistrate level and 304 were above the prefecture
commissioner level, including the former secretary of Beijing's
Municipal Party Committee, Chen Xitong.
</P>
<P>
In dealing with these cases successfully, discipline
inspection departments recovered 4.66 billion yuan (about 560
million U.S. dollars) in what would otherwise have been losses,
Wei reported.
</P>
<P>
The country had canceled the collection of 9,000 unreasonable
fees of various kinds aimed at farmers by the end of October,
reducing farmers' burdens by 6.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 21,000 kinds of fees levied on enterprises were
stopped, saving them a total of 80 billion yuan, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
