<HEADLINE> German Wins Giant Slalom of Snowboarding World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- German Markus Ebner won the men's
giant slalom of the snowboarding world championships in
Berchtesgaden, Germany on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ebner, second after the first leg, won by more than a second
in a combined time of two minutes 12.28 seconds, beating France's
Maxence Idesheim to second in 2:13.36 and Austrian Stefan
Kaltschuetz third in 2:13.83.
</P>
<P>
However, reigning champion Thomas Prugger of Italy skied out
in the first leg on the hard, icy Goetschen piste, and Olympic
champion Ross Rebagliati of Canada dropped out of contention by
losing over two seconds in a shaky first run.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Nicolas Huet, who led after the first leg, fell on
the lower part of the course in the second leg. He managed to
complete his run but finished outside the top five.
</P>
<P>
Ebner burst into the limelight by scoring his first World Cup
win in a parallel giant slalom last week in Morzine, France.
</P>
</TEXT>
