<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile to Intervene in UK Pinochet Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 13 (Xinhua) - Britain's highest court on
Wednesday granted Chile the right to be represented in a
rehearing of whether former leader Augusto Pinochet enjoys
immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
"It would be wrong for them to be excluded." Lord
Browne-Wilkinson, chairman of a House of Lords appeal committee,
said after granting Chile's application.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer for the Chilean government, Laurence Collins, said
he would argue in the rehearing that Pinochet, as a former head
of state, has immunity under international law from facing
charges of torture, murder and kidnap.
</P>
<P>
"It is absolutely elementary under international law that only
the state has the right to waive immunity," Collins said.
</P>
<P>
The rehearing was made possible by Pinochet's lawyers after
they argued to the House of Lords that one of the five judges,
who ruled in November by three to two that Pinochet was not
immune from prosecution, had close connections with the human
rights group Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
The rehearing on Pinochet's immunity is scheduled for next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 83, is now under police guard in a mansion in the
suburb of London. A Spanish judge accused him of responsibility
for the death and disappearance of 3,000 people during his
1973-1990 rule, and wanted him extradited to Spain to face
charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
