<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Returns From Three-Nation Europe Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi returned here Tuesday afternoon after wrapping up an
eight-day visit to France, Italy and Germany.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, which took place soon after the European
single currency euro was launched, Obuchi campaigned for a
tripartite financial world divided by the dollar, the euro and
the yen, and for governments to move to ensure exchange rate
stability.
</P>
<P>
In talks with leaders of the three European countries, Obuchi
also sought their cooperation to control fluctuations among the
three major currencies.
</P>
<P>
Hidden beneath the call for cooperation, analysts pointed out,
was Japan's fear that the yen may be relegated to a local
currency in the shadows of the euro and dollar. 
</P>
