<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mount Batur in Indonesia's Bali Again Spews Out Smoke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Mount Batur in Indonesia's Bali
has again spewed out white smoke and red-hot blaze and sent off
the smell of lava, but it is yet to pose a danger to the community
living around it.
</P>
<P>
"To avoid any uncalled for matters, however, domestic and
foreign mountaineers are not allowed to climb this mountain
temporarily. The mountain is on an alert status," third assistant
to Bangli regional secretary Wayan Suarka told Antara News Agency
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the thick smoke the mountain spewed out Tuesday
afternoon was visible from Kintamani, a tourist resort, followed
by a strong smell of sulfur blown everywhere by quite a strong
wind.
</P>
<P>
The red-hot blaze spewed out from the crater in the western
part of the mountain was originally hot smoke that the mountain
has been sending out in the past few year.
</P>
<P>
Recently, however, the hot smoke has gotten thicker and thicker
and gone up higher and higher, interspersed with the spewing out
of red-hot blaze, particularly during the night when it can reach
as high as 25 meters.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the belching out of thick smoke, coupled
sometimes with the spewing out of red-hot blaze, the western part
of the mountain foot is now covered with black dust, just like
what happened when the mountain erupted in the middle of 1997 and
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mount Batur offers tourists a beautiful natural panorama which
brings together a mountain, a valley and a lake, all alluringly
visible from Kintamani, some 50 kilometers to the northeast of
Denpasar, capital of Bali province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
