<HEADLINE> British Judges Hear New Applications on Pinochet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 13 (Xinhua) - Three top British judges began
hearing lawyers' applications on Wednesday into whether former
Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet is entitled to immunity from
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The judges from the House of Lords, Britain's highest court of
appeal, were hearing applications from lawyers representing the
Chilean government and human rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers were asking for permission to intervene in the
case, which is due to come before Britain's highest court on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Last November, Five law lords ruled 3-2 that 83-year-old
Pinochet, currently living under police guard in a mansion in the
suburb of London, was eligible for extradition to Spain despite
his status as a former head of state.
</P>
<P>
But the House of Lords, in an unprecedented move last month,
overturned its own verdict when Pinochet's lawyers argued that
one of the five judges had close links with human rights group
Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet was arrested in a London hospital on October 16 while
recovering from minor back surgery.
</P>
<P>
A Spanish judge accused Pinochet of being responsible for the
deaths and disappearances of more than 3,000 people during his
17-year rule in Chile, which ended in 1990, and wanted the
retired general to be extradited to Spain to face charges.
</P>
<P>
However, Pinochet said in a London court in December that he
does not recognize any court outside Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
