<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libya to Take Important Steps on Lockerbie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- An official of Libyan Ministry of
Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation has said that Libya
is to take important practical steps toward a solution to the
Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made after talks between Libyan officials
and Prince Bandar Ibn Sultan, special envoy of Saudi King Fahd,
and Jakes Gerwel, envoy of South African President Nelson Mandela,
Tuesday evening, Libyan News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official said wide discussions have been made and all
parties concerned entertained the goodwill to cooperate in search
of a solution.
</P>
<P>
Consultations and efforts in this direction are ongoing to
overcome the existing obstacles facing the trial of two Libyans
suspected of bombing a U.S. passenger plane over Lockerbie,
Scotland, in 1988, leading to the death of 270 people, the
official said without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Following the talks, Prince Bandar said "we are currently
trying to help lift the embargo on Libya for good, and our visit
to Libya is in support of the brotherly Libyan people."
</P>
<P>
But he did not tell the content of the initiative of Saudi
Arabia and South Africa he brought here to push the Lockerbie
issue toward a final solution to totally lift the embargo.
</P>
<P>
The agency said Gaddafi has agreed to a second round of talks
Wednesday for further discussions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. slapped an air-travel ban on Libya in 1992 after
Libyan leader Moammar Gaddafi refused to surrender the two
suspects for trial in the U.S. and Britain, saying they will never
get a fair trial in either country.
</P>
<P>
A compromise was made when the U.S. and Britain agreed the
suspects can be tried in the Netherlands before a panel of
Scottish judges according to Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
Libya has agreed in principle to turn over the suspects, but
said arrangments should be made beforehand for their security and
if convicted, they should serve their prison terms in Libya.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who has good relations with the Libyan leader, talked
with British Prime Minister Tony Blair during his visit to South
Africa on January 6 on the Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi envoy has reportedly close connection with
Washington. The two envoys arrived at Tripoli international
airport on a Saudi jet Tuesday afternoon, which was granted a
special permission to fly into Libya by the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has decided that the sanctions will
be suspended once the two suspects are surrendered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
