<HEADLINE> China, S.Korea, Japan Vow to Cooperate in Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Environmental ministers of South
Korea, Japan and China Wednesday agreed here to strengthen
cooperation to prevent further environmental pollution in Asia's
Far East.
</P>
<P>
"We share the view that three-way cooperation in the field of
environment is extremely important and indispensable because
dynamic economic development has been deteriorating the regional
environment," South Korean Environment Minister Choi Jae-wook
told a news conference after a tripartite meeting with Manabe
Kenji of Japan and Xie Zhenhua of China.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the three ministers reached an eight-point
agreement to tackle the region's environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the ministers will place top priority in
areas such as air and sea pollution, the protection of the marine
environment and biological diversity, and the development of
environmental technology.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministers, who are concerned about ecological
damage wrought by development projects throughout the region,
agreed to establish an open channel for exchanges of information
and to meet annually.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of environment ministers was the first of its kind
between the three nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
