<HEADLINE> Hyundai Gets Exclusive Right to Develop DPRK's Mount Kumgang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Hyundai Group has
been guaranteed the exclusive right to develop the Kumgang
Mountain into a tourist resort in the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang promised to grant Hyundai exclusive rights to build
and use various facilities, including hot springs, ski resorts,
and hotels in and around Mount Kumgang on DPRK's east coast for
more than 30 years, Kim Yoon-kyu, chief of Hyundai's North Korean
Project, said on arrival in Seoul from China Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have received confirmation of the guarantee from the North
Korean Asia-Pacific Peace Committee and a North Korean trader who
is involved,'' said Kim, who discussed the controversial
guarantee with DPRK officials in Beijing early this week.
</P>
<P>
The document guaranteeing Hyundai's exclusive rights will be
delivered later from the DPRK's Asia-Pacific Peace Committee.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government did not authorize Hyundai's
revised Mount Kumgang project due to the DPRKs' early refusal to
offer a written guarantee to the group.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to deposit 25 million U.S. dollars in a North Korean
bank account in a third country, possibly in China, upon
receiving the approval from the Unification Ministry (of South
Korea) on the revised application for the development project,''
said Kim.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK threatened to halt the development of Mount Kumgang
tourism if Hyundai did not pay the 25 million U.S. dollars
immediately for the exclusive right before the promised deadline.
</P>
<P>
The payment of the 25 million dollars will be the first
installment of the 940 million dollars Hyundai has promised to
pay over the next six years for allowing South Korean tourists to
visit Mount Kumgang.
</P>
<P>
However, Hyundai failed to pay the sum due to the South Korean
government's refusal to authorize the revised application.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government is expected to meet Thursday to
give the green light to Hyundai for its Mount Kumgang project and
the payment of 25 million dollars to the DPRK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
