<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Parliament to Discuss Confidence Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Lower House of Nepali
Parliament will discuss Thursday a confidence motion tabled by
Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala on January 1, Speaker Ram
Chandra Poudel told the house session Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Poudel expressed the hope that all political parties would help
conduct the house proceedings in a very systematic manner.
</P>
<P>
He said earlier that the main agenda of the winter session of
parliament was the vote of confidence in the government.
</P>
<P>
Koirala said that the government is committed to making
upcoming elections free and fair, and all parties should cooperate
for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
"If all parties join the government, it will be helpful to set
an example in international forum," he said.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of the tri-partite government formed in late
December 1998, the sixth since the mid-term polls in November
1994, is to conduct free, fair and impartial elections by
March/April 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached in December 1998 between the Nepali
Congress and the Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML), the two main ruling partners, in order
to form a national government for elections, the government is
open to other parties represented in parliament which are wishful
to enter.
</P>
<P>
The faction of the National Democratic Party (RPP) led by
former prime minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand has talked with the
ruling parties over its entry into the coalition.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that after winning the vote of confidence in the
house, Prime Minister Koirala will ask King Birendra to dissolve
parliament for fresh polls. Usually the winter session of
parliament in Nepal lasts for two months.
</P>
<P>
As it enjoys a majority in the house, there will be no problem
for the government to obtain the confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
The present coalition was formed after the
three-and-half-a-month coalition between the Nepali Congress and
the Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) broke up
in December 10, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Now the CPN-ML is the main opposition party in parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
