<HEADLINE> South Australia to Further Cooperation with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua)-- With the announcement of
several key initiatives that have been put into place, Premier of
the State of South Australia John Olsen said here today that his
current trip in China has been "valuable" with "productive and cor
dial" talks with relevant government departments.
</P>
<P>
Olsen met with Premier Zhu Rongji yesterday and he described
the meeting as significant since it shows the importance of South
Australia to the Government of China.
</P>
<P>
According to him, South Australia-based Architect Woodhead
International have won a 55 million US dollar contract to develop
and preserve a key residential district in Shanghai. "The
intention with this project is to preserve the historical
character and texture of the existing area which has an estimated
population of 4,000 and comprises 65,000 square meters. It will
also provide valuable export revenue for South Australia." he said
</P>
<P>
Also, a South Australian company is selling its library
automation system to the Shanghai Library - the second largest in
China, and a number of Shanghai universities are using this
package.
</P>
<P>
South Australia Water has signed a Memorandum of Understanding
with the Shanghai Municipal Waterworks focusing on exchange of
expertise and the provision of technology.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, South Australia will open a commercial
representative office in Beijing, with similar offices already
set up in Jinan, Shanghai and Hong Kong. The state will also help
establish a new hospitality and hotel training school for 500
students for the Beijing hotel chain.
</P>
<P>
South Australia will look for more co-operative opportunities
with China in the educational, manufacturing, and the mineral
processing sectors, and explore more business opportunities
between South-Australia based companies and their Chinese
counterparts, he added.
</P>
<P>
South Australia, one of the six states of Australia, covers
about 984,000 square kilometers and hosts a population of 1.5
million. China, overtaking Japan, stood as the state's largest
export market last year. Its major export products are grain,
wool and minerals. 
</P>
