overseas markets, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index tumbled 24.3 points to
2822.0, recovering from an intra-day low of 2806.3.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average index succumbed
to profit-taking after its bullish New Year's run, sliding 145.21
points to 9474.68.
</P>
<P>
On Australian equities markets, the all industrials index
toppled 52.3 points to 5043.9, while the all resources index
firmed 0.8 points to 1011.8.
</P>
<P>
The banking index dropped 86.7 points to 6436.6, with NAB
sliding 64.5 cents, Commonwealth falling 33.4 cents and ANZ
retreating 21 cents, while Westpac added five cents.
</P>
<P>
Australian National Industries topped the turnover table, with
44.33 million shares traded.
</P>
<P>
Telco stocks followed the negative trend on the broader market,
with Telstra retreating six cents, Cable &AMP; Wireless Optus easing
one and AAP dropping 14 cents.
</P>
<P>
News Corp tumbled 27 cents and its preferred scrip slid 36.
</P>
<P>
Among resource stocks, BHP added 0.9 of a cent, Rio Tinto
gained 10.9 cents, WMC gained 4.9 and MIM firmed one cent.
</P>
<P>
The gold index slipped 16 points to 1130.3.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold in Sydney closed at 288.05 U.S. dollars an
ounce, down from the close of 292.05 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 487.11 million shares traded for 1.36
billion Australian dollars (863.6 million U.S. dollars), with
falling stocks outnumbering rising stocks 705 to 493 and 434
stocks remaining steady. 
</P>
