<HEADLINE> 1,700-year-old Tower No Longer Leans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A 1,700-year-old tower in
downtown Shanghai recently saw its leaning come to an end under
the careful supervision of local experts.
</P>
<P>
The ancient brick-and-wood tower, built during the Three
Kingdoms Period (220 - 265), had been tilted by 50 centimeters,
the Shanghai-based Xinmin Evening News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lack of renovation had brought about the tower's weathering
and cracking to the point where it leaned to a gradient of 4.73
percent, or eight times the acceptable degree, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The local government has pledged to carefully monitor the
tower while landscaping work for a new entertainment center
nearby is underway.
</P>
<P>
Experts directed workers to consolidate the tower base and
prevent it from tilting even further, and architects will keep
the tower under close observation.
</P>
<P>
Municipal authorities also plan to alter the major road
passing through the area near the tower, the newspaper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
