<HEADLINE> Urban Families Plan Automobile Purchases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey revealed that
four out of every 1,000 urban families in China plan to buy
private cars, with the potential market standing at 103,000 units.
</P>
<P>
Beijing and Guangzhou led the list of 12 cities with seven o
ut of 1,000 families planning to buy private cars.
</P>
<P>
The survey covered 48,704 families in Beijing, Shanghai,
Tianjin and Guangzhou, as well as Chengdu in the southwest,
Shenyang in the northeast, Jinan, Fuzhou and Nanjing in the east,
Wuhan in central China, Xi'an in the northwest and Kunming in the
southwest.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's edition of Investment Weekly published by the
Economic Information Daily listed the results of the survey
jointly conducted by Chinese, British and U.S. research
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Only three out of 1,000 families in Shanghai, China's leading
industrial city, listed private cars on their shopping lists.
</P>
<P>
"Auto" model vehicles produced by a Sino-Japanese in Shanghai
was the first choice for the majority of respondents. The model ca
rries a manufacturer's price of 5,783 U.S. dollars. Mercedes
Benz models, which retail for between 96,400 - 482,000 U.S.
dollars, ranked second.
</P>
<P>
Some 206,000 Beijing families currently own automobiles,
followed by Guaangzhou with 103,000 private owners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
