<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Recovers Tax Defaults </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China recovered defaulted tax
payments of over 20 billion yuan in 1998, according to figures
released during the on-going national work conference on taxation.
</P>
<P>
Twelve billion yuan of the total involved defaulted taxes
payable before last year, with the figure accounting for 36
percent of the pre-1998 amount outstanding.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China accelerated efforts to determine
the actual amount of overdue taxes, with the effort yielding tax
payments of over 46 billion yuan. Tax departments collected 15.7
billion yuan more than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Taxation departments at all levels strengthened the clamp down
on tax evasions. Over 2.24 million businesses were charged with
tax evasion during 1998. The recovery of evaded taxes increased
revenues by 2.33 billion yuan on 1997.
</P>
<P>
China's tax revenues for 1998 hit 850 billion yuan, up 100
billion yuan on the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
