<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Solicits Public Opinion on Contract Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The NPC chairman said the law should provide solutions for
"triangular" and overlapping debt which continue to plague the
Chinese economy, as well as protect the economy from the adverse
impact of the ongoing financial crisis engulfing most of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Discussions during the seminars focused mainly on the validity
of verbal contracts, and the fine line between unpredictable
external changes and normal business risks.
</P>
<P>
The current draft law only recognizes the validity of written
contracts, including fax and e-mail agreements, and the status of
verbal contracts must be settled forthwith.
</P>
<P>
Industry leaders voiced approval for related stipulations and
noted the difficulty in verifying verbal contracts. They also
noted that the new rule will help to reduce the number of
contract disputes.
</P>
<P>
"Safety should be the priority, but efficiency must not be
ignored," according to Jiang Ping, a professor at the University
of Politics and Law.
</P>
<P>
The law should recognize verbal contracts which are commonly
used by small businesses, said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Gao Hongbin, president of a local court in east China's
Zhejiang Province, said that courts have in most cases partially
recognized the validity of verbal contracts. He added that it
would be inappropriate for the law to make verbal contracts
illegal.
</P>
<P>
Jurists and attorneys suggested detailed additions to address
different situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Countries Urged to Create More Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A tripartite meeting of labor
specialists and employment planners on Wednesday urged Asian
countries to create more jobs in an effort to prevent social
unrest.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Deputy Minister of Labor and Social Welfare Jongchai
Thiengtham told the opening session that creating jobs should be a
policy priority of Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Delegates representing employers, workers and governments from
12 countries were attending the meeting, organized by the
International Labor Organization (ILO).
</P>
<P>
"Employment is no longer likely to be viewed as an automatic
outcome of economic growth. It is likely to be viewed as a policy
priority in its own right," said Jongchai.
</P>
<P>
He said that for many countries in the crisis-struck region
"the greatest shortfall has been in the mechanisms and
institutions of social protection and social security".
</P>
<P>
Jongchai stressed the need for social dialogue at a time when
"sacrifices need to be made and there are and will continue to be
job losers".
</P>
<P>
He said that Asia's traditional strengths of high economic
growth rates and export orientation needed to be built upon,
notably by enacting "employment policies and strategies aimed at
developing human resources to respond to labor markets".
</P>
<P>
The technical report prepared for discussion at the meeting
depicted a gloom employment situation across the region, with no
country immune to job losses.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, some 8 million jobs were lost in 1998 and the
unemployment rate could rise as high as 20 percent. In Thailand
and South Korea, the crisis sent unemployment figures from 2.2
percent to 5 percent and from less than 3 percent to 7 percent
respectively. In the Philippines, unemployment is estimated to be
at least 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the transition economies of East Asia (such as Laos and
Vietnam) and South Asian economies (Bangladesh, Nepal, Pakistan
and Sri Lanka), job quality was deteriorating, forcing people back
into casual employment and subsistence agriculture. Neither were
the developed economies unaffected by unemployment -- Japan's rate
had gradually risen to 4 percent, while in Australia and New
Zealand, rates had hovered around 8 percent in recent years.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting which runs from January 13-15, delegates are
expected to recommend measures to spur job creation, emphasizing
human resource development, social dialogue and development
planning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 120,000 Corrupt Party Members Penalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Some 124,000 corrupt Communist
Party of China (CPC) members had been penalized by the end of
November of 1998, according to the CPC Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection.
</P>
<P>
The CPC has 50 million members.
</P>
<P>
According to the commission's third plenum which opened here
today, discipline inspection departments across the country had
received more than 1,612,000 reported cases of corruption by the
end of November of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The departments investigated 142,000 cases and brought 120,000
of them to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Of the penalized Party members, 3,970 were officials at the
county magistrate level, and 304 were above the prefecture
commissioner level, including the former secretary of the Beijing
Municipal Party Committee, Chen Xitong.
</P>
<P>
By successfully dealing with these cases, discipline
inspection departments recovered 4.66 billion yuan (about 560
million U.S. dollars) in what would otherwise have been economic
losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Solicits Public Opinion on Contract Law (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With regard to introducing the legal principle of "rebus sic
stantibus", legal and economic experts expressed concern about
the difference between the overwhelming changes in external
circumstances which are beyond the control of debtors and market
fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed concern about protecting the legitimate
interests of Chinese businesses in the foreign trade arena when
the new principle becomes part of the law.
</P>
<P>
"Rebus sic stantibus" refers to the rights of debtors when
unpredictable changes in social and economic situations affect
the execution of contracts and negotiations with creditors
concerning contract terms, as well as seeking arbitration or
court rulings.
</P>
<P>
Li said the new law should address the risk of major
fluctuations in the exchange rate to effectively reduce financial
risks.
</P>
<P>
Participants also discussed whether or not the technology
contract law should be separated and allowed to co-exist with the
new contract law. They pointed out that the Ministry of Science
and Technology has issued comprehensive administrative decrees
regarding implementation of the law.
</P>
<P>
Members of the judiciary welcomed the 60 pages of special
provisions contained in the draft law, and noted that judges will
have detailed rules to follow when handling related cases.
</P>
<P>
Various participants questioned the ubiquitous right of
government departments to supervise contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swaziland's Telephone System in Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBUR, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland's telephone
service has unexpectedly been in chaos after its telecommunication
department opened a new phone numbering system on January 1, South
African daily Business Day reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners, perplexed at their inability to reach Swaziland by
telephone, have swamped Swazi journalists and government officials
with e-mailed inquiries about whether a coup had taken place.
</P>
<P>
The caller chaos has resulted in financial losses to businesses
and industry, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, two-digit area code prefixes
have been added to existing five-digit numbers. The Swaziland Post
and Telecommunications Corporation announced the change in local
newspaper advertisements, but did not inform international callers
through pre- recorded messages. As a result, callers from outside
Swaziland found old numbers ringing indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Richards, managing director of the telecommunication,
was quoted as saying that the new numbering system "was put in
place to meet international standards. Foreign phone companies
were told of the change in plenty of time, and it was their duty
to inform their customers."
</P>
<P>
Locally, there is widespread ignorance regarding the new
system, which Richards blames on "a culture where nobody reads".
Those dialling old numbers receive recorded messages saying "the
dialled number does not exist" , and advising that an information
operator be contacted.
</P>
<P>
However, many callers complained that information operators
were frequently unavailable, and some calls to correctly dialled
new numbers did not go through.
</P>
<P>
Hardest hit financially has been Swaziland's tourism industry.
"We have lost bookings and customers cannot confirm bookings," a
hotel operator in the Ezulwini Valley complained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
