<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebel Leader Agrees to Cease Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The rebel leader of Sierra Leone
Foday Sankoh has said that he was willing to sign a truce if he is
freed and his Revolutionary United Front (RUF) is recognized by
the Sierra Leonean government, a senior U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. special representative Francis Okelo made the remarks
Tuesday night in Guinean capital of Conakry following a three-hour
meeting between Sankoh and West African mediators, according to
reports reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. official, Sankoh expressed his
willingness to order a cease fire and recognize the legitimacy of
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah during the closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
"He is 100 percent committed to peace," Okelo was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Okelo noted that West African mediators of Togolese Foreign
Minister Joseph Kokou Koffigoh and his Cote d'Ivoire counterpart
Amara Essy would present Sankoh's terms to President Kabbah, and
try to arrange a face-to- face talk between Sankoh and Kabbah in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh who was sentenced to death by a Sierra Leone court last
October and in government custody until recently was flown from
his jail to neighboring Guinea for talks with mediators on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In Freetown, witnesses said bodies littered the most streets of
the city following seven days of fighting between the West African
peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG and the rebels who once
controlled parts of the central and eastern city.
</P>
<P>
"The rebels are burning and destroying everything in sight as
they retreat" after the ECOMOG troops launched their offensive on
Sunday, one witness said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR), Kris Janowski told a news briefing in Geneva that "a
humanitarian disaster is looming in the capital (of Sierra Leone)
unless some kind of ceasefire is arranged and humanitarian
supplies can be brought in."
</P>
<P>
"The situation is quite terrifying for civilians. People are
holed up, and are not in a position to move out of their homes,
let alone flee the capital," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
