<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Issues Directive on "Traveller Pets" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's Ministry of
Agriculture has issued a directive requiring foreigners entering
or leaving the country to produce health certificates for the
domestic animals they carry with them, according to Wednesday's
English newspaper "the Ethiopian Herald".
</P>
<P>
Wondwosen Asfaw, an officer from the ministry said Ethiopia has
 introduced the measure in fulfilment of its obligation as a
member of the International Veterinary Organization.
</P>
<P>
He said, Ethiopians or foreigners entering or leaving with
cats, dogs or other pets are required to produce vaccination
certificates for the animals, adding that the measure is intended
to curb the spread of communicable disease from one country to the
other through these animals.
</P>
<P>
Wondwosen said passengers carrying pets with them on airplanes
should realize that all airlines require them to produce health
certificates for their animals.
</P>
<P>
He reminded travellers abroad to visit the Ministry of
Agriculture to collect these certificates before embarking on
their journeys. 
</P>
