<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Test-tube Baby Technology Helps Infertile Become Fathers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A 36-year-old Chinese woman
is now three months pregnant after undergoing intro vitro
fertilization (IVF) and embryo transfer.
</P>
<P>
This case was rare in today's China, not because of the woman,
but because of her husband who was suffering from an obstruction
in his spermatic duct which prevented the normal ejaculation of
sperm.
</P>
<P>
They were among the first group of 12 Chinese couples who have
benefited from a new test-tube baby technology introduced from
the United States, known as intracytoplasmic sperm injection
(ICSI) and non-surgical sperm aspiration (NSA).
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of all males with poor-quality semen suffer
from spermatic duct obstruction. But NSA now can help them
produce healthy sperm, and ICSI has helped make their wives
become pregnant, said Wang Yun of the Shanghai Ji'ai Genetics &AMP;
IVF Institute - China USA Center.
</P>
<P>
The center, jointly established four months ago by the
Shanghai Hospital of Gynecology and Obstetrics and the Genetics &AMP;
IVF Institute of the U.S., is the only in China providing such
services, Wang Yun told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
The exact number of males in China suffering from poor-quality
semen remains unknown, but for every 100 couples of child-bearing
age, ten are infertile, and one can have their own babies only
through test-tube technology, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"Since the country's population is so large, the number of
couples needing these services is also expected to be quite
significant," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to this new technology, many infertile men will be
able to have their own children, instead of borrowing the sperm
of others," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
