<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swaziland's Telephone System in Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBUR, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland's telephone
service has unexpectedly been in chaos after its telecommunication
department opened a new phone numbering system on January 1, South
African daily Business Day reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners, perplexed at their inability to reach Swaziland by
telephone, have swamped Swazi journalists and government officials
with e-mailed inquiries about whether a coup had taken place.
</P>
<P>
The caller chaos has resulted in financial losses to businesses
and industry, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, two-digit area code prefixes
have been added to existing five-digit numbers. The Swaziland Post
and Telecommunications Corporation announced the change in local
newspaper advertisements, but did not inform international callers
through pre- recorded messages. As a result, callers from outside
Swaziland found old numbers ringing indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Richards, managing director of the telecommunication,
was quoted as saying that the new numbering system "was put in
place to meet international standards. Foreign phone companies
were told of the change in plenty of time, and it was their duty
to inform their customers."
</P>
<P>
Locally, there is widespread ignorance regarding the new
system, which Richards blames on "a culture where nobody reads".
Those dialling old numbers receive recorded messages saying "the
dialled number does not exist" , and advising that an information
operator be contacted.
</P>
<P>
However, many callers complained that information operators
were frequently unavailable, and some calls to correctly dialled
new numbers did not go through.
</P>
<P>
Hardest hit financially has been Swaziland's tourism industry.
"We have lost bookings and customers cannot confirm bookings," a
hotel operator in the Ezulwini Valley complained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Cabinet Prepares to Fight Y2K Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is studying
to mobilize security forces in the first week of January 2000 to
ensure the maintenance of law and order during the transition
period while the effect of the Y2K bug becomes clear, a government
minister said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Jay Naidoo, minister of Posts, Telecommunications and
Broadcasting Department, told a press briefing in Pretoria that
the cabinet had discussed this mobilization possibility.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Year 2000 Decision Support Center in
Pretoria, the readiness level for government-owned enterprises is
34.59 percent and for the public sector 30.45 percent.
</P>
<P>
Three government departments -- Arts, Culture , Science and
Technology, Correctional Services and Communications, said that
they had completed their Y2K projects while the remaining
departments expect to complete them late in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Naidoo said Deputy President Thabo Mbeki was driving the
efforts of government on Y2K issues.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki had informed directors-generals in writing that it was
their responsibility as head of provinces and departments to
ensure Y2K compliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
