<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Surgeons Help Cataract Sufferers in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Surgeons from military
hospitals in the Chinese capital have performed over 1,000
operations on cataract patients in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The team is participating in the Sight First China Action
program which will dispatch 250-odd medical teams to rural and
remote areas over the next five years to carry out 1.75 million
cataract operations.
</P>
<P>
The program is jointly sponsored by the Ministry of Health,
China Federation of Disabled Persons and Lions Club International
(LCI). The LCI alone has donated over 15 million U.S. dollars to
the project.
</P>
<P>
Cataracts have blinded over four million Chinese citizens, or
almost half of the total number of blind people throughout the
nation.
</P>
<P>
Tibetans face a much greater risk of cataracts due to high
altitude and strong ultraviolet rays in the Tibet Autonomous
Region. The incidence rate for cataracts in Tibet is twice as
high as in other regions in China, with Tibetans generally
cataracts between 10-15 years earlier than people in other areas.
</P>
<P>
The lack of medical facilities and inconvenient transportation
infrastructure in the region multiply the seriousness of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
The program's first mission to Tibet between mid-August and
mid-September was the most extensive rehabilitation program in
the history of the Tibet Autonomous Region, according to Minister
of Health Zhang Wenkang.
</P>
<P>
The medical team also supplied the region surgical facilities,
artificial lens and medicines valued at 800,000 yuan (about
99,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Wang Chengjin, an official with the aforementioned federation,
said the sponsors plan to arrange more medical aid programs to
help cataract sufferers in Tibet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
