<HEADLINE> Chinese Divers Call Shots at Diving World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- With excellent and
precision performances, Chinese Zhou Yilin and Liang Xiaoqiao
made their ways to victory in the men's one-meter and woman's
three-meter finals of the 11th Diving World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four divers from 16 countries and regions competed in
the men's one-meter event, with six entering the finals this
evening at the Wellington Regional Aquatic Center.
</P>
<P>
Except for two finalists from China, others were from Germany,
the United States, Australia and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
China's 24-year-old Zhou Yilin, who was ranked third at the
previous Diving World Cup, perfectly executed his sixth and last
dives, and scored 88.74 points, the highest points in today's
competitions, paving his way to winning the gold medal in the me
n's one-meter event.
</P>
<P>
Zhou's compatriot Wang Tianling won the silver medal and
Andreas Wels of Germany the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
Many countries pay great attention to the three-meter diving
because it is one of the Olympic events. Twenty-nine divers from
17 countries and regions, including several world champions such
as Russia's Irina Liashko and Yulia Pakhalina, Canada's Myriam
Boileau and Ukraine's Olena Zhupina, contended for the top honor
of the woman's three-meter event today.
</P>
<P>
The competition went on very intensively. After the
preliminary and semi finals, six divers including two from China
entered the finals this evening.
</P>
<P>
In face of so many experienced divers, China's 14-year-old
Liang Xiaoqiao was fearless. She excellently performed her five
dives, winning the gold medal with an accumulated score of 294.72
points. Emilie Heymans of Canada scored 274.62 points, winning
the silver medal, and China's Guo Jingjing ranked third with
272.97 points.  
</P>
</TEXT>
