<HEADLINE> Karl Marx Manuscript Found in Beijing Library </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China's oldest and most
important library announced today that for at least 40 years it
has been the custodian of original letters written by Karl Marx
and Frederick Engels.
</P>
<P>
"We have a private letter from Marx to his daughter and a
letter from Engels to a friend of his," said Huang Runhua, chief
of the rare books department of the National Library, in an
interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Few people knew these historic manuscripts were in the
library, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Huan Xiang, a diplomat serving in the Chinese Embassy in
London, enthusiastically collected hand-written letters he
obtained from roadside used-book stalls and local auction houses
in 1950s. The state allocated his collection to the National
Library for preservation, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
These letters were well-kept in the library's most advanced
stack room, where humidity and temperature remain constant.
</P>
<P>
The letters, written in black ink, are still very clear, said
Huang.
</P>
<P>
Ranking fifth among the world's libraries in number of
volumes, China's 90-year-old National Library has some 270,000
rare books and 35,000 ancient bones and tortoise shells with
inscriptions.
</P>
<P>
It also has a copy of the earliest version, in Latin, of the
works of Copernicus, published in 1566.
</P>
<P>
The library's huge collection obviously underscores its
prominent position, Huang added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
