<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Releases Result of State Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Independent National
Electoral Commission (INEC) of Nigeria has released the final
result of last Saturday' s state governors and legislators
elections.
</P>
<P>
According to the result announced in Abuja Tuesday by INEC
Chairman Ephraim Akpata, the People's Democratic Party (PDP) won
the governorship in 19 states, the All People's Party (APP) in
nine and the Alliance for Democracy (AD) in six, said local press
reports Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
By-election will be held in Rivers State Saturday as the
results there are "inconclusive", Akpata told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
In the State House of Assembly elections, the PDP won 528
seats, the APP 251 and the AD 166, he said, adding that
by-elections will be held in a few constituencies where elections
could not hold or were disrupted.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's elections were not held in the Bayelsa State in the
southeast, because of the recent spate of violence there.
</P>
<P>
According to the INEC result, a total of 24,649,434 persons
voted in the elections, which accounted for 46 percent of the
53,161,687 registered voters.
</P>
<P>
Akpata said the elections were largely free and fair and
acceptable to Nigerians, from what he has read in the press and
the reports of both local and international observers.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the United Nations and the Commonwealth for their
assistances in the deployment of logistics and training of INEC
staff, and reiterated the INEC's commitment to the success of
elections remain.
</P>
<P>
According to the transition to civil rule program announced by
the military government, Nigeria will hold the national
legislators and presidential elections in February, while its
first elected civilian president in 15 years will be sworn in on
May 29, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
