<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Flys to France on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
Ariel Sharon flew to Paris Wednesday morning for talks with his
French counterpart Hubert Vedrine on the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
During his four-day visit, Sharon will explain to Vedrine
Israel's position on the Wye River peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Sharon's visit is apparently designed to appease France's
displeasure with Israel for not moving ahead with West Bank troops
pullbacks laid down under the Wye deal, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
Accusing the Palestinians of failing to fulfill their
commitments in the Wye deal, Israeli government froze the accord
in early December after conducting the first of the three phases
of troops deployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The current impasse has not only delayed the troops withdrawal,
but also put the Israeli-Palestinian final status talks on hold.
</P>
<P>
According to Oslo accords, the final status talks should have
been started by May 1996 to tackle the thornist issues such as the
fate of Jerusalem, the refugees and borders.
</P>
<P>
A permanent peace deal should be signed between Israel and the
Palestinians by May 4,1999 before a five-year interim period
expires. But the two sides have been locked into land disputes so
far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
