<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roth: Jiang-Clinton Exchange Marks Positive Accomplishment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. official said
here Tuesday that the exchange of visits by the presidents of
China and the United States was the first positive accomplishment
of the Clinton administration's Asia-Pacific policy.
</P>
<P>
Stanley Roth, assistant secretary of state for East Asia and
Pacific affairs, told a press conference at the Foreign Press
Center that one could not minimize the significance of President
Bill Clinton's trip to China last June, which followed President
Jiang Zemin's visit to the U.S. in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
"This was a very important event in trying to, not only
establish and maintain momentum in U.S.-China relations, but to
try to give meaning to the notion of moving towards a
constructive strategic partnership," said Roth.
</P>
<P>
Roth accompanied Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on
several trips to the East Asian and Pacific region last year.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of visits by Presidents Jiang and Clinton
demonstrated that "the ability of the United States and China to w
ork together on a range of issues would be crucial for managing
many of the regional and global challenges that confront us."
</P>
<P>
"Despite all the problems that remain -- and I make no effort
to minimize it in the U.S.-China relations -- I thank that the su
mmit was a major step forward," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Roth joined the China critics in pressurizing Beijing
for human rights improvements. In March, some Congressmen urged
the administration to sponsor anti-China resolution at the Geneva
U.N. human rights meeting.
</P>
<P>
"On China, even though I put it in the success category, which
I do, I think it's also obvious, as I mentioned before, that
there have been setbacks, most notably recently on human rights
issues," Roth said.
</P>
<P>
The American lawmakers stepped up criticism of China following
the recent detention of some criminals who had attempted to
subvert the government.
</P>
<P>
The China critics and human rights advocators have urged the
administration to postpone the planned human right dialogue with
China, but the State Department refused to heed the call.
</P>
<P>
On Monday and Tuesday, Chinese Assistant Foreign Minister Wang
Guangya and his American counterpart Harold Koh held closed
meetings in the State Department to discuss the human rights
issue. But nothing was made public so far.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to address the issue separately Wednesday
after the end of the two-day negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Roth hailed the resumption of dialogue between China's
mainland and Taiwan, believing the negotiations have some
prospects.
</P>
<P>
"I think one of the final major accomplishments would be
resumption of cross-straits dialogue between Taiwan and the PRC
(People's Republic of China), which I believe was a major
development and had some prospects that we should be encouraging
for the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States have signed three joint
communiques regarding Taiwan, committing the U.S. to One-China
policy. But Congress enacted a law called "the Taiwan Act"
shortly after Beijing and Washington established diplomatic relati
ons on January 1, 1979, allowing U.S. arms sales to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on suggestions that the Taiwan Act came
before the three joint communiques in relations with Taiwan, Roth
said that it involved a legal question and what is more important
was to make the resumed cross-straits dialogue a success.
</P>
<P>
He urged the two sides across the Taiwan Strait to take steps
to build mutual trust and to narrow their differences through
negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
