<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Re-urged to Resume Inter-Korean Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Wednesday
re-appealed to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
to accept its offer to resume the inter-Korean government-level
talks.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government is willing to conclude a contract u
nder which it will grant fertilizer, pesticide, vinyl and other
materials necessary to the DPRK to cultivate plants like tobacco
and import them back, Vice Unification Minister Jeong Se-hyuneong
said at a forum on inter-Korean relations.
</P>
<P>
"Those issues can be discussed at government-level talks
between the two Koreas," he said at the forum, which was
organized by the presidential Advisory Council on Democratic and
Peaceful Unification.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister indicated that the government will not
attach tough conditions to assistance to the DPRK if Pyongyang
restores dialogue with Seoul.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike the Beijing talks last year, we need to be flexible in
our negotiations on aid to the North," he said.
</P>
<P>
Official inter-Korean talks held in Beijing last April for the
first time in nearly four years to discuss Seoul's fertilizer aid
to Pyongyang broke down after Seoul put the reunion of separated
families as a condition for assistance to the DPRK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
