<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anwar's Lawyers Plan to Call Malaysian PM as Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The defense in former
Malaysian deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim's corruption trial
said Wednesday it plans to call Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
and three other Cabinet ministers as its witnesses.
</P>
<P>
The defense plans to call Mahathir to testify at the trial
together with Finance Minister Tun Daim Zainuddin, International
Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz, Domestic Trade and
Consumer Affairs Minister Megat Junid Megat Ayob and former
inspector-general of police Abdul Rahim Noor, if the court orders
Anwar to enter his defense, Anwar's defense counsel Christopher
Fernando told the High Court here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Fernando made the application to call the witnesses after
Senior Deputy Public Prosecutor Abdul Gani Patail offered the
defense 47 witnesses who are on a list and said that the
prosecution would make available witnesses not listed.
</P>
<P>
The defense however decided to call 22 witnesses from the list,
and Rafidah who is not listed.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Gani Patail told the court that the prosecution was
wrapping up its case on the four corruption charges against Anwar
whose trial, which began on November 2, 1998, entered its 45th day
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During trial, the prosecution has called 23 witnesses.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, 51, is charged with abusing his position by interfering
in police investigations into allegations of sexual misconduct
against him.
</P>
<P>
The court has ordered the defense and the prosecution to submit
Thursday and will decide whether to call Anwar to enter his
defense after both sides have finished their submissions at the
end of prosecution's case.
</P>
<P>
Justice S.Augustine Paul, presiding over the case, Wednesday
allowed the prosecution to amend the four charges against Anwar in
terminology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
