<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4th International DAB Symposium Opens in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 13 (Xinhua) -The 4th International Digital
Audio Broadcasting (DAB) Symposium opened Wednesday with a view to
exchange information on DAB technology and to advance
implementation of strategy on DAB services and business.
</P>
<P>
DAB is the radio technology which allows sound, text and
picture to be digitized -- from transmission to reception. It
enables interference free, CD quality sound with no need to retune
or remember a station's frequency. This three-day symposium is
jointly organized by the World DAB Forum, a non-governmental
organization, and the Singapore Broadcasting Authority.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister of Information and the Arts George Yeo
delivered a key-note speech at opening ceremony participated by
more than 250 delegates from 27 countries and areas.
</P>
<P>
Yeo said digitization has led to rapid changes both in
broadcast technology and the broadcast environment and there is a
growing interest in digital broadcasting in Asia.
</P>
<P>
He also announced Singapore will introduce commercial DAB
service this year after more than a year of preparatory work.
</P>
<P>
There is a packed program for this symposium and speakers will
talk about latest information about DAB development across the
world.
</P>
<P>
Emphasis is believed to be laid on starting DAB services,
regulating them, making and launching consumer receiver products
and the business aspects.
</P>
<P>
The World DAB Forum holds a symposium every two years and the
Third Symposium was held in Montreux in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
