<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Plans to Export More Labors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has planned to send some
20,000 to 25,000 laborers to work abroad this year, Vietnam's
English daily "Vietnam News" reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese labor export will be expanded not only in existing
markets such as Japan, South Korea and the United Arab Emirates,
but also to new markets, including Taiwan, Hong Kong, Brumei, the
Middle East and Africa.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Vietnamese government planned to seek new
contracts on labor export in Eastern European countries such as
Russia, Moldova, Azerbaijan and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
However, due to a lack of capital, Vietnam's Dau Tu
(Investment) newspaper said, Vietnamese labor export businesses
faced difficulties in researching new labor export markets and
promoting existing ones.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics of Vietnam's Ministry of Labor, War
Invalids and Social Affairs, the number of Vietnamese laborers
sent to work overseas decreased dramatically in 1998. Vietnam's
labor export businesses sent nearly 10,300 people to work abroad,
a mere 60 percent of the 1997's figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
