<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Zambian President Warned to Back out From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Chief government spokesman
Newstead Zimba said former President Kenneth Kaunda should
immediately stop receiving his terminal benefits if he has any
moral conscience and recognizes the law which provides for the
facility.
</P>
<P>
Zimba told journalists Tuesday that Kaunda "can not remain in
politics and have the benefits at the same time because he is
aware of the law regarding benefits for former presidents."
</P>
<P>
He said Kaunda's insistence on continuing with party politics
and hoping to assume republican presidency would be contrary to
the constitution which stipulates that one can only serve as
president for two consecutive five-year terms.
</P>
<P>
Zimba, who is also Minister for Information and Broadcasting
Services, was reacting to reports quoting Kaunda as having said
the law was designed to hinder his political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
Zambian newspaper, the Post, Wednesday quoted the former
president as saying in an interview with the British Broadcasting
Corporation (BBC) in London that he "would not retire from active
politics soon because current events in Zambia's political arena
would not warrant that."
</P>
<P>
Kaunda said Tuesday that he would contest the Zambian
presidency in 2001. And he would continue leading his party, the
United National Independence Party (UNIP), until his followers
decide he had to leave.
</P>
<P>
The 74-year old veteran politician ruled the country for 27
years and was defeated by incumbent President Frederick Chiluba in
1991.
</P>
<P>
It is said that Kaunda and the government has concluded an
agreement under which he will get all his retirement benefits as a
former president on condition that he retires from active
politics.
</P>
<P>
However, he has not handed a letter of resignation to the party
 secretary-general as required by the party constitution if he
wants to retire before his term of office expires by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to force Kaunda to retire, the Zambian parliament
endorsed last September the Benefits of Former President Amendment
Bill which states that a former president would lose his benefits
if he participates in active politics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
