<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1999 Wolf Prize for Medicine, Chemistry Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Israel's 1999 Wolf Prize for
Medicine will be awarded to Vienna-born professor Eric Kandel,
Columbia University, New York, the Wolf Foundation has said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 1999 Wolf Prize for Chemistry will go to
Raymond Lemieux, professor of the Alberta University, Canada.
</P>
<P>
Professor Kandel, 69, was awarded for the elucidation of the
organismic, cellular and molecular mechanism, whereby short-term
memory is converted to a long-term form.
</P>
<P>
How learning occurs and memory is stored, is one of the
major questions central to both neural science and congnitive
psychology. Kandel has helped to demystify the study of learning
and memory storage, by delineating the molecular mechanisms
underlying these processes. In so doing, he has discovered the
molecular swith whereby labile short-term memory is converted into
stable long-term memory maintained by structural changes.
</P>
<P>
Kandel has shown how the the methods of psychology can be
merged with those of biology to endow the study of behavior and
learning with renewed vigor and explanatory power. His work has
influenced the way both biologists and pychologists now think
about these processes.
</P>
<P>
Kandel received his B.A. degree from Harvard University and
his M.D degree from New York University. Between 1968-1974,
Kandel served as chief of the Department of Neuro-Biology and
Behavior of the Public Health Research Institute of the City
of New York and as senior Research Psychiatrist and Director
of the Laboratory of Neuro-Psychology of the Massachusetts Mental
Health Center. He has been associated with Columbia university
since 1974.
</P>
<P>
Lemieux, 78, earned his award for his fundamental and
seminal contributions to the study and synthesis of
oligosaccharides and to the elucidation of their role in
molecular recognition in biological systems.
</P>
<P>
Lemieux's contribution to the study of the chemistry of
carbohydrates has led to a transformation of the discipline,
providing the pillars upon which present-day oligosaccharide
chemistry and biochemistry now rest.
</P>
<P>
The Wolf Prize was established in 1978 by the late
German-born Ricardo Wolf, who lived in Cuba for many years and
served as Cubian ambassador to Israel. The Israel-based Wolf
Prize is awarded to outstanding scientists and artists for
achievements in the interest of mankind and friendly relations
among peoples.
</P>
<P>
The annual Prize, which amounts to 100,000 U.S. dollars in each area,
are given in four out of five scientific fields, namely
agriculture, chemistry, mathematics, medicine and physics. In the
arts, the prize rotates among architecture, music, painting and
sculpture.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 prizes will be conferred by President Ezer Weizman
in a special ceremony to be held at the Israel parliament, on
May 2, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Wolf prize recipients in Physics and Mathematics will be
announced on January 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
