<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Supports Dialog for Pan-Arab Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 13 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi official spokesman
said Wednesday that Iraq is for equal dialog under the umbrella of
supreme Arab interests and for the sake of pan-Arab security.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made the statement following Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein chaired a meeting of high-ranking officials Tuesday
night on the latest developments of the political situation, the
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
No details of the meeting was given by the agency, but
observers here believe that the spokesman was directing at the
forthcoming Arab foreign ministers' meeting scheduled for January
24, during which Iraqi issue will top its agenda.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said equal dialog under umbrella of the supreme
Arab interests could lead to practical solutions to the different
or contradictory positions and ideas.
</P>
<P>
He added that this kind of dialog should be conducted in a
manner expressing attitude of the Arab masses and the pan-Arab
security.
</P>
<P>
Iraq recently stepped up a rhetoric campaign against Kuwait
and Saudi Arabia, alleging that the two Gulf neighbors should be
accountable for the damages and casualties caused by U.S. and
British air strikes against the country in mid December.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said that cruise missiles fired by the U.S. and British
forces passed through Kuwaiti airspace and more than 100 warplanes
flew over Saudi Arabia and Kuwait during the raids. So Iraq
preserves the right for compensation for damages.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Arab Gulf states including Kuwait and Saudi
Arabia strongly rejected the Iraqi threat and insisted on Iraq's
implementation of all U.N. resolutions related to its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said that to seriously reach solutions
serving the Arab nation, the pan-Arab security should be
considered as part and parcel and to consider any aggression by
any foreign party on any Arab country as tantamount to an
aggression on the Arab Nation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"The matter necessitates a clear-cut and certain stand by the
Arab officials by condemning and denouncing the U.S.-British
aggression against Iraq," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting were Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadhan, Deputy Premier Tariq Aziz, parliament Speaker Sadoun
Hammadi, Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf and Information
Minister Abdul Khaleq, said INA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Major Decline in Exports Makes Annual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan, which has long been
beset with economic difficulties, is experiencing a major decline
in its exports, making the annual export target difficult to
achieve.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures by the Federal Bureau of Statistics show that
despite unprecedented incentives, Pakistan's export earnings
during the first half of the 1998-99 fiscal year (July 1,1998-June
30,1999) stood at 3.84 billion U.S. dollars only, down 12.4
percent from the same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
In view of the 10-billion-dollar export target for the current
fiscal year, with a 5-billion half-year target, exports have
lagged behind the official projection by 1.16 billion dollars so
far.
</P>
<P>
To catch up with the annual target, Pakistan needs to export
1.02 billion dollars worth of goods each month for the remainder
of the current fiscal year. But exports in the first half of
1998-99 averaged only 640 million dollars per month.
</P>
<P>
Most worrisome to the government is the drop of textile exports
which fell considerably by 14 percent during the first half of the
fiscal year to 2.43 billion dollars compared with 2.85 billion
dollars in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's textile industry plays a pivotal role in the
country's export sector. As the figures by the Federal Bureau of
Statistics show, textile products made up 64 percent of the total
exports of 3.84 billion dollars during the first two quarters of
the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the textile industry said that of the many textile
products, cotton yarn and fabrics are main products of exports and
these two products in Pakistan are fast losing their international
market shares to India and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the decline trend in the export
sector will make the annual export target too hard to achieve.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pakistan has trimmed its import bill by 1.07 billion
dollars in the six-month period after enforcing a tight policy of
providing minimum foreign exchange to importers.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that during the first six months of
1998-99, the value of imports decreased to 4.396 billion dollars
from 5.472 billion dollars in the same period of 1997-98 with a
major drop in wheat and machinery imports.
</P>
<P>
However, due to declines both in exports and imports,
Pakistan's trade deficit declined to 594 million dollars during
the first two quarters of the current fiscal year, as against 1.13
billion dollars in the same period of 1997-98, showing an
improvement of 536 million dollars or 47.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif had hoped that
with enhanced exports it would be able to take care of the
dramatic shortfall in revenue.
</P>
<P>
However, with the major decline in exports, it seems to be
unrealistic that the expected revenue target for the current
fiscal year could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
The Central Board of Revenue is most likely to post a net
revenue collection of only 305 billion rupees (6.6 billion
dollars) during fiscal 1998-99, which is almost 50 billion rupees
(1.08 billion dollars) less than the original budgetary estimates
of 354.6 billion rupees (7.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The expected revenue indicates a shortfall of nearly 28 billion
rupees (608 million dollars) from the agreed benchmark of 333
billion rupees (7.23 billion dollars) with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Analysts here are of the view that with the IMF and the World
Bank still reluctant to make any definitive commitment about their
relief or bailout package for Pakistan and with no sign of
recovery in the export sector, Pakistan's economic prospects in
the near future will remain dim. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
