<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Egyptian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Egyptian newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Al Ahram:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa Tuesday briefed
President Hosni Mubarak on his visit to Israel Monday. During his
visit, Moussa urged the Israeli government to implement the Wye
River accord.
</P>
<P>
The latest Palestinian-Israeli peace deal, signed in last
October in Washington, was suspended in early December by Israel,
which said the Palestinian side has not done enough to curb
violence against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Al Akhbar:
</P>
<P>
-- Eight persons were killed and 14 others injured Monday night
when soccer fans rushed for stands in Arab Alexandria stadium to
see a match between local teams.
</P>
<P>
The security forces in the resort town of Alexandria had
brought the situation under control and victims were hospitalized,
said an official source at the interior ministry.
</P>
<P>
Deaths resulted from fatal chest injuries and skull concussion
in the crowds' stampede, said authorities.
</P>
<P>
Al Gomhuria:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian Foreign Minister Moussa Tuesday dismissed as
completely incorrect the reports that he had called for a new
leadership to replace the incumbent Iraqi regime.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Egypt does not interfere in the domestic affairs of
any other country and the local peoples are the only entitled to
decide who rule them.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Gazette:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will travel to
Saudi Arabia and Egypt later this month for talks on Iraq and the
Middle East peace process, her spokesman said late Monday. 
</P>
