<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, January 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albanian Defense Minister Luan Hajdaraga and his
Italian counterpart Carlo Scognamiglio said here Tuesday that the
Kosovo issue should be solved through political dialogue and
talks.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint press conference after their meeting,
Hajdaraga said that it is the Albanian government's stand that no
force should be used to alter the current boundary of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Scognamiglio, for his part, said that Italy supports the
political settlement of the Kosovo issue within the framework of
respecting Yugoslavia's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
(Albania-Italy-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SOFIA - Bulgaria's structural reform will be more or less
finished by the end of 1999 and as will its aligning process to
European legislation, President Peter Stoyanov said on Tuesday at
a get-together with foreign diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov also hoped the military reform, involving
introduction of civilian control over the armed forces to meet
the standards of NATO member states, will also be completed at tha
t time. (Bulgaria-Reform)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- France, one of the permanent members of the
United Nations Security Council, on Tuesday initiated U.N. talks
on a new policy towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In a closed meeting with U.N. ambassadors from the other four
permanent members of the council -- China, Russia, the United
States and Britain -- French Ambassador Alain Dejammet proposed
to loosen U.N. sanctions against Iraq and ease up the arms
inspection regime. (France-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin on Tuesday
congratulated Nursultan Nazarbayev on being re-elected president
of Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
In his letter of congratulations, Jiang said: "Upon your being
re-elected president of Kazakhstan, I, on behalf of the Chinese
people and in my own name, offer you my sincere congratulations
and best wishes." (China-Kazakhstan-Congratulations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- Britain still views its relations with Zimbabwe as
cordial despite recent assertions by Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe that it was leading in criticism against the country
abroad, British High Commissioner to Zimbabwe Peter Longworth
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Longworth said while the two countries disagreed "now and
then" on some issues, it was natural although both nations hoped
the disagreements were not often.
</P>
<P>
"We have a good thriving relationship with Zimbabwe. Where we
fall out occasionally is on policy," he told journalists at a
news conference. (Britain-Zimbabwe-Relations) 
</P>
