<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti-Iraqi Ties to be Restored if Saddam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Parliament Speaker
Ahmad Al-Saadoun has said Kuwaiti-Iraqi ties will be normalized if
the incumbent Iraqi regime is toppled, the Kuwaiti Arab Times
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"None of us expected the Saddam (Hussein) regime to occupy
Kuwait. Now five years after the border demarcation between the
two states, we hear officials of the Iraqi regime renewing claims
that Kuwait is part of Iraq," Al-Saadoun said at a seminar of
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, some Iraqi lawmakers called for scrapping a
U.N. resolution 833, which demarcates the Iraqi-Kuwaiti border in
1993, two years after the Gulf War in 1991 set off by Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The resolution "is without precedent, unfair and arbitrary,"
said the Iraqi lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait National Assembly (parliament), in a hit-back
statement Tuesday, deplored the Iraqi move, terming it "a flagrant
violation to the U.N. Charter and to the Security Council
resolutions."
</P>
<P>
The assembly expressed concern on the continued "non-commitment
of the Iraqi regime to the international resolutions" and held it
"responsible for the sufferings of its people."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi regime should also be held accountable for the
rupture and diaspora the Arab nation is suffering, the statement
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
