<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientist Cites Impropriety of "Solar Terms" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Phenologist Wan Minwei said
here today that traditional "solar terms" are outdated due to the
climate change.
</P>
<P>
 Solar terms lasting approximately 15 days each divide the
lunar year into 24 periods with names which indicate obvious
changes in nature at the particular time. Wan, a member of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), said that ancient Chinese
farmers planted crops according to solar terms. However, the
modern solar calendar features fixed solar terms which fail to
recognize annual climate changes. "The modern solar calendar is
inappropriate for modern agriculture," according to the
nonagenarian phenologist.
</P>
<P>
 Wan said dividing the year according to phenology and
temperature would be more practical for agriculture. He added
that the phenology changes on a yearly basis and could be used as
seasonal index. Wan also suggested the development of a natural
calendar with phenological periods for plants, animals and
crops.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
