<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 08:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Eases Travel Limits on Palestinian Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has eased the tight
travel restrictions imposed on Palestinian refugees residing in
the country.
</P>
<P>
"The general directory of the General Security decided to
consider Lebanese travel documents granted to Palestinians living
in Lebanon as passports," a government statement issued Tuesday
said.
</P>
<P>
The General Security, however, later issued a clarification,
saying that Palestinians still need clearance to travel, but
that the permits will henceforth be valid for six months and
enable their bearer multiple trips within that period.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that previously Palestinians needed exit and
re-entry visas for every trip.
</P>
<P>
The government statement said the decision is the result of
talks on the issue between Lebanese leaders and Farouk Kaddoumi,
head of Palestinian Liberation Organization's Political
Department who visited the country last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Some 350,000 Palestinians live in 12 refugee camps across
Lebanon. They are denied the right to work in some 75 occupations.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian source said further measures, including the
lifting of the working ban on Palestinians in Lebanon, will come
out soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists to Relocate Rare Dolphins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are looking
for the best method to protect the Yangtze River white-flag
dolphin, the most endangered species of dolphin in the world,
with fewer than 100 living in the middle and lower reaches of the
Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The number of such dolphins is shrinking due to the rapid
development of fishing, shipping, water conservation and
pollution in the river, according to today's Guangming Daily.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that since these adverse factors cannot be eradi
cated in the short term, the only solution is to move the
dolphins to a nature reserve with a natural environment similar
to their original habitat.
</P>
<P>
They have chosen some possible sites in Hubei and Jiangxi
provinces, both along the middle reaches of the Yangtze, and have
begun to raise black-finless porpoises there, which are similar
to the Yangtze's white-flag dolphins.
</P>
<P>
Unlike pandas, the Yangtze River dolphins are difficult to
catch and raise. A white-flag dolphin swims at speeds up to 60
kilometers an hour, while the boats used to catch them for
relocation at the nature reserve sail at only 15 kilometers an
hour.
</P>
<P>
The white-flag dolphin also requires a quality environment
including clean water with low-germ content and adequate fresh
food to survive.
</P>
<P>
Several leading scientists at the Chinese Academy of Sciences
have already called on relevant departments urging them to spend
more money and manpower on the rare dolphins, which face possible
extinction within 25 years if they are not better protected than
they are now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
