<HEADLINE> Cholera Claims 13 Lives in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Cholera has killed 13 people and
plagued another 711 in Mozambique in the past five days, an
official with the health authorities of the southern African
country said.
</P>
<P>
Avertino Barreto, Assistant Director of the National Health
bureau said Tuesday at a press conference that cholera has hit all
the 11 provinces but Inhambane Province in the southern part of
the country, the Noticias daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The worst-hit provinces are the Nampula and Cabo Delgado
provinces in the northern part of the country which are in their
raining seasons.
</P>
<P>
Rainwater, which has drained excrement and urine everywhere,
has spread cholera virus to residential areas and thus
contaminated some wells. Barreto said that about 1,841 people have
died of the disease since it broke out in August 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
