<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Turns Into Major Magnet for Mineral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Explorers
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has become the
largest country in Sub-Saharan Africa in terms of attracting funds
from foreign explorers for non-ferrous minerals, the Minister of
Energy and Minerals, Abdallah Kigoda, has said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, international explorers spent 57.7 million U.S.
Dollars on Tanzanian mines, or 13.2 percent of the total in
Sub-Saharan Africa, a newspaper published here quoted Kigoda as
saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure has outweighed Ghana which ranked second in this
regard, the minister told the Financial Times in an interview last
week.
</P>
<P>
The minister cited Tanzania's political stability and
prevailing peace, changed government policies in favor of private
sector as well as a prospective geographical terrain, as major
factors contributing to the growing flow of capital.
</P>
<P>
He said the Kahama Mining Corporation Ltd, a subsidiary of
Sutton Resources of Canada, has discovered some 239.5 tons of gold
deposits in Kahama District, in northern Shinyanga Region. The
company plans to open an underground mine with projected annual
output of 9.3 tons of gold.
</P>
<P>
Other companies like De Beers, Anglo-American Prospecting
Services, Arusha Planters and Traders are hunting for diamond,
nickel, cobalt and uranium, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
