<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some European Nations Agree on Peacekeeping Force in Balkan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Defense ministers from seven
southern and eastern European countries Tuesday signed a
supplementary protocol towards the creation of a multinational
peacekeeping force in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Defense ministers from Albania, Greece, Bulgaria, Italy,
Macedonia, Slovenia and Romania, along with representatives from
the United States and Turkey, agreed to rotate the headquarters
of the future force every four years in four countries: Bulgaria,
Romania, Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters of the force is expected to begin operation
this summer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, participating countries hoped the force to conduct
its first military exercise by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Under the framework of the protocol, the force's command will
be rotated among member states every two years, with Turkey being
the first candidate followed by Greece.
</P>
<P>
The force, 3,000 to 4,000 men, created to bring stability to
the Balkan region, was agreed upon last September at a meeting of
the region's defense ministers in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Macedonia will join it as observers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
