<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prince Ranariddh Favors Trial of Khmer Rouge Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prince Norodom
Ranariddh said Wednesday that he prefers trying Khmer Rouge
leaders outside the country but called for waiting for the United
Nations' decision.
</P>
<P>
"In the name of social justice, I favor to try the Khmer Rouge
leaders. The King Norodom Sihanouk also supported it," Ranariddh,
president of the National Assembly, told reporters at the Faculty
of Dentist in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
"The question whether to amnesty them or not, I think it's
better to let out high legal bodies of the National Assembly and
the soon-to-be-created senate to decide," he added.
</P>
<P>
The persons the prince referred to for trial include top Khmer
Rouge leaders Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, who defected to the
government last month.
</P>
<P>
International pressures are mounting recently on the government
and Prime Minister Hun Sen to arrest and try the pair for "their
crimes against humanity."
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said earlier that "for the interest to put an end to
the Khmer Rouge organization and for national reconciliation, we
have to leave a tribunal case of Khmer Rouge leaders for the time
being."
</P>
<P>
Sar Kheng, deputy prime minister and interior co-minister, also
insisted that ending the protracted civil war is a higher priority
than bringing Khmer Rouge leaders to trial. "For the government,
the first priority is peace and ending the war," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh said while he prefers the court be set up outside
Cambodia, he does not oppose trying the Khmer Rouge leaders at
home if most Cambodian people insist, but pointed out that the
trial should be carried out by international legal experts in
accordance with the international law.
</P>
<P>
Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, the two high-profile former Khmer
Rouge leaders, are now living in the western town on Pailin, a
former stronghold of Khmer Rouge and a gem-rich area near the Thai
border. It is reported that the pair worried over calls for a
tribunal and had left Pailin "to the Thai border." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
