<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Donates Hepatitis Vaccines to Flood Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Lazaro Herrera, minister
counselor of the Embassy of Cuba, announced today that the Cuban
government will donate a shipment of hepatitis B vaccines valued
at 1.15 million US dollars to areas in China hit by record summer
flooding last year.
</P>
<P>
The vaccines will be used to prevent outbreaks of the
hepatitis B virus in the Yangtze River Valley in east China and
along the Songhua and Nenjiang rivers in the northeast, according
to Yin Dakui, vice-minister of Health. Yin noted that the related
departments have closely monitored and effectively prevented the
spread of infectious diseases over the past several months.
</P>
<P>
Some 120 million Chinese citizens, or 10 percent of the
country's total population, are HBV carriers. China plans to
increase inoculation efforts to lower the incidence rate for the
virus to one percent within the next 50 years, with special
emphasis to be place on related programs in rural areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
