<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qingdao to Invite Bids for Building Designs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The coastal city of Qingdao, a
major tourist destination in east China's Shandong Province, will
invite bids for the designs of major public buildings which will
be constructed in the future in an effort to add more color to
the city's appearance.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Chuankang, an official in charge of city planning in
Qingdao, said that public bidding will be arranged for
competitors from both home and abroad for the design of every
large public building from now on.
</P>
<P>
"We need advanced concepts as well as creative designs," Zhao
said.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao is famous for its variety of buildings, including
those in Greek, Japanese and Chinese styles, which were built in
recent centuries and have earned the city a reputation as an
"architectural museum."
</P>
<P>
To protect these historic structures, the city has been
developing a district on its eastern outskirts for new high-rises
since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The city government has also laid down a series of
regulations, stressing that all buildings erected in the urban
areas should be in line with the city's original style and
features.
</P>
<P>
The city is now working out a program for enhancing
international exchanges in architectural design. 
</P>
</TEXT>
