<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Upgrades Bangladesh's Loan Rating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has placed Bangladesh under a new classification of loan recipient
countries, a leading English daily newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's position to receive ADB loan has moved up from the
"eligibility to interest-free loans only" category to one eligible
for a mixed basket of interest-free and interest-bearing loans
under the new classification, The Independent quoted a source in
the Finance Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka's reclassification in ADB's loan portfolio became
effective from January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The reclassification of Dhaka's position did not take place all
of a sudden, the source said, adding that the donor agencies such
as the World Bank and the ADB had been watching the steady rise in
the country's export earnings over the past years and took into
account Dhaka's capacity for debt serving.
</P>
<P>
This reclassification has opened an additional loan window, and
now Bangladesh would be able to borrow interest-bearing loans,
which are administered from a different window known as the
Ordinary Capital Resource (OCR), according to a source in the ADB
Dhaka office.
</P>
<P>
He, however, pointed out that the OCR falls in the category of
hard loan which is less concessionary. Bangladesh is eligible now
to draw from this fund if the government so desires, he added.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that ADB's total loan commitment to
Bangladesh so far stands at 2.5 billion U.S. dollars, of which 1.2
billion dollars are now in the pipeline. There are about 36
on-going projects and the annual disbursement against them is
around 250 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
