<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Cooperatives Play Big Role in Rural Financing System (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China's rural credit
cooperatives, which celebrate their 50th anniversary this year,
have been playing an increasingly important role in the rural
financial system, according to a senior official of the People's
Bank of China (PBOC).
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics released by the country's central bank,
show that by the end of September 1998, the total assets of
rural credit cooperatives had amounted to 1.55 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding amount of deposits in rural credit c
ooperatives had reached 1.17 trillion yuan, accounting for 12.7
percent of the total deposits in all financial institutions,
while the outstanding loans by rural credit cooperatives was
829.3 billion yuan, accounting for 10 percent of all the loans
extended by financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Compared with 1977, when China first began its reform and
opening policies, the deposits and loans of rural credit
cooperatives have increased by 72 times and 208 times,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that some 80 percent of loans to farmers
and 70 percent of loans to township enterprises have been
extended by rural credit cooperatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Cooperatives Play Big Role in Rural Financing System (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's rural credit cooperatives were organized by farmers
who voluntarily bought shares in them when the People's Republic
of China was founded in 1949. In the 1950s and 1960s these
cooperatives played a significant role in financing farmers'
production and improving their life-styles. Over the recent 20
years, they have experienced fast development along with the
rural economy.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the cooperatives were separated from the Agricultural
Bank of China, which enabled their standardization to take place
in accordance with the principles imbued in real cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At present China has more than 50,000 independent such
cooperatives with staff totaling 650,000, representing one
administrator per one thousand farmers.
</P>
<P>
The director of the central bank's department for supervising
cooperative financial institutions, Zhang Gongping, said that
there are still difficulties and problems in their management due
to certain policies or organizational and management reasons.
</P>
<P>
A considerable number of credit cooperatives are suffering
from a deteriorating asset quality and operating losses, while
some have become insolvent.
</P>
<P>
In early 1998, the central bank announced that it intended to
step up supervision on the cooperatives and would try to
introduce a more effective and efficient system within three
years. Pilot programs were then carried out in ten counties to
try and alleviate the financial risk suffered by the cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
Zhang added that the on-going changes planned for the
cooperatives will focus on those that are insolvent or at high
risk, as well as in improving financial supervision, the internal
control mechanisms and the support given to agricultural
production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Plants Saved as Snow Batters Kunming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of rare plants,
which will be a highlight of the 1999 World Horticulture Expo to
be held in May in Kunming, have been saved by 3,000 local
policemen and civilians from a freak snow-fall which hit the city
last week.
</P>
<P>
Many of the trees and flowers transplanted into the "expo
garden" in southwest Yunnan's capital, are precious, valuable and
from tropical locations; hardly able to cope with the unexpected
cold snap. They were covered with straw in a desperate bid to
keep them alive.
</P>
<P>
In the city, traditionally renowned for its permanent
Spring-like weather, more than fifty bonfires were lit by the
local fire brigades to provide warmth for the special flowers,
trees and other plants which could easily die because of the
cold.
</P>
<P>
And local workers assisted by soldiers were forced to move
more than 10,000 valuable plants out of the expo's fifteen
greenhouses, which were destroyed by the snow storm.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday the snow stopped and sunshine began to melt the ice
, much to the relief of the expo organizers who have worked hard
to meet the deadline - and the quality of the displays - for the
event. Now they plan to re-build the greenhouses and move the
plants back in.  
</P>
</TEXT>
