<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firework Ban Remains in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's Deputy Mayor has
vowed to enforce the ban on firecrackers in the city during the
traditional Spring Festival which begins on February 16.
</P>
<P>
Meng Xuenong's ruling came as an illegal firecracker plant in
rural east Anhui Province blew up over the weekend killing 14
people and seriously wounding three others.
</P>
<P>
He has ordered all public security organs and fire brigades to
be vigilant and prevent fires as a result of fire-crackers during
the most important of Chinese holidays.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese capital has recently suffered a series of
disastrous fires, which resulted in heavy financial losses. The
latest conflagration, last week, completely destroyed the city's
largest lamp market in the southwestern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
Since December 1993, when Beijing introduced the ban, fewer
people have been injured by firecrackers, which have been a
traditional Chinese way of celebrating festivals for centuries,
and there have been far fewer fires.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from local hospitals show that they received an
average of 1,380 patients injured by crackers every year during
the five years leading up to the ban but only 521 patients were
hospitalized a year later.
</P>
<P>
However, many people are resentful of the ban because they
insist firecrackers add to the enjoyment at festival time and
have called for the municipal government loosen their ruling. And
some other big cities across China have resumed the firework
custom after years of prohibition.
</P>
<P>
But Beijing's local authorities and legislative body have
reiterated the firm stance they have taken against allowing the
setting off of firecrackers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
