<HEADLINE> Relations With Zimbabwe Cordial: British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain still views its
relations with Zimbabwe as cordial despite recent assertions by
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe that it was leading in
criticism against the country abroad, British High Commissioner to
Zimbabwe Peter Longworth said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Longworth said while the two countries disagreed "now and then"
on some issues, it was natural although both nations hoped the
disagreements were not often.
</P>
<P>
"We have a good thriving relationship with Zimbabwe. Where we
fall out occasionally is on policy," he told journalists at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
In his new year message, President Mugabe accused Britain of
leading the band wagon of criticisms and malicious statements
against his government instead of taking the front seat in
promoting its programs.
</P>
<P>
But Longworth said Britain was one of the donor countries which
wished to see Zimbabwe succeed in every sphere of development and
was actually doing so through various developmental projects it
supports in the country.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat denied Mugabe's argument that British companies in
Zimbabwe repatriated large amounts of their profits to Britain
each year yet, in comparison, the aid Zimbabwe got from the
European country was a pittance.
</P>
<P>
On the contentious land issue in Zimbabwe, Longworth said
Britain supported land reforms which were aimed at alleviating
poverty without impacting on agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to allocate resources once the first inception
phase agreed on at the land conference starts," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the war in the Democratic Republic of Congo, in which
Zimbabwe has intervened in support of President Laurent Kabila's
government, Longworth said his government was behind all efforts
to bring peace to the country.
</P>
<P>
"We support the withdrawal of foreign troops and signing of a
ceasefire agreement. We have interest in seeing peace and
stability in Africa," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
