<HEADLINE> China Boosts Anti-Smuggling Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China plans to clamp down on
the smuggling of pornographic and illegal publications this year,
as well as intensifying its campaign to smash the racket in
pirated discs and videos.
</P>
<P>
Publishing houses across the country will be inspected and
those without an official license will be shut down. And those
found to have been involved in illegal publishing will also face
criminal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
Unregistered wholesale book markets and shops and stalls
selling audio-visual material will be closed
</P>
<P>
According to a report in today's People's Daily, Beijing
authorities seized 22,204 copies of pirated books and 83,305
discs over a five-day period last week. While south China's
Guangdong Province closed down three warehouses stacked with
smuggled and illegal products and seized 400,000 discs in one day
alone in Guangzhou City.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou will now cooperate with Hong Kong in trying to stamp
out the rampant smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Over the next few weeks, southwest, northwest and northeast ar
eas of China are also planning to destroy batches of illegal
audio-visual products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
