<HEADLINE> Klim Named as Australian Swimmer of The Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Multiple world champion
Michael Klim was named 1998 Australian Swimmer of the Year on
Wednesday, according to reports from Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Klim, who won a record seven medals at the 1998 world
championships in Perth, won the award ahead of a strong field
including Ian Thorpe, Susie O'Neill and Grant Hackett.
</P>
<P>
Klim was named by swimming's world governing body FINA as the
swimmer of the meet after he won four golds, including two
individual titles, at Perth in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
He also set two short-course world records for 100 meters
butterfly in the same day at a World Cup meet in Sydney before
his form fell away later in the year.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Swimming Australia said the selection was the
hardest in the 10-year history of the award because of the
quality of nominations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
