<HEADLINE> Turkish Army Chief Praises Military Ties with Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Turkish Chief of
General Staff Hussein Kivrigouglu said he was happy with the
decision to station the Multinational Peace Force of Southeastern
Europe (MPFSEE) in Plovdiv, the second largest city in Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to framework for a regional multinational
peacekeeping force agreed in Athens Tuesday by defense ministers
of seven southern and eastern European states.
</P>
<P>
Under the framework, command of the MPFSEE will be rotated
between members states every two years with Turkey taking charge
in August 1991, followed by Greece.
</P>
<P>
Kivrigouglu, who arrived here Tuesday for a three-day official
visit, told reporters that cooperation between the Bulgarian and
Turkish military on Bulgarian territory will strengthen bilateral
relations and enhance peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He did not rule out the possibility that the Balkan
peacekeeping force may intervene in the Kosovo crisis in case of
deterioration of the situation and following the adoption of the
relevant decision by NATO.
</P>
<P>
Kivrigouglu voiced hopes that a naval force twin to the land
force will be set up in the region of the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, he is scheduled to visit the command of the
rapid reaction forces in Plovdiv. 
</P>
</TEXT>
