<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Nobelist Calls on Mexico to Adopt US Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Gary Becker, United States
Nobel Economics Prize winner, suggested Mexico adopt the U.S.
dollar to avoid recurrent financial crisis due to Mexico peso's
periodic devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Becker said that Mexico's monetary system should be
permanently reformed through a monetary council to avoid exchange
rate crises such as the 1994 currency collapse, newspapers quoted
Becker as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Becker, born in 1930, was awarded the 1992 Nobel Prize in
economics for his research that extended economic theory to areas
of human behavior.
</P>
<P>
He noted that without permanently aligning the peso at a fixed
rate with the dollar, Mexico will continue to be affected by
world financial turbulence, even though its monetary policy is st
abilized.
</P>
<P>
Becker also recommended that Mexico continue its economic
reforms, boost deregulation and privatization in a bid to attract
more foreign investments and capitals.
</P>
<P>
Exchange markets instability due to a world financial crisis
pushed Mexico's inflation rate to a staggering 18.6 percent last
year, much higher than the predicted 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Wobbling exchange rates prompted a debate in Mexico's
financial sectors whether the peso should be linked to the
dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Bengal Tigers Decreasing in Sundarbans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The population of Bengal tigers,
one of the world's most magnificent animals, is decreasing rapidly
following poaching and shrinking of livable spaces inside the
Sundarbans, which is located in southwestern Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
According to registered cases between 1976 to 1985, the annual
average of tiger killing was 12 while in the year 1997 to 1998
some nine tigers were killed in the area, leading researcher
Professor Anwarul Islam of the Zoology Department of Jahangirnagar
University was quoted by The Daily Star newspaper Wednesday as
saying at a seminar.
</P>
<P>
Since the turn of this century, the habitat and number of
Bengal tigers have been reduced by up to 95 percent, said Islam,
who is now leading a research team to study the ecological
requirements of the Bengal tiger in the Sundarbans.
</P>
<P>
Tiger poaching was continuing everywhere in the Sundarbans, the
largest mangrove forest in the world, and there are allegations
that some of the forest officials have connections with the
poachers, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Tiger skin, though not easily available, was sometimes
illegally sold in the Dhaka and Chittagong markets, he alleged,
adding that tiger teeth, claws and purses made from tiger skins
were also sometimes sold illegally in tourist shops in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
Tiger is protected here by third schedule of the Bangladesh
Wildlife Preservation Act, 1974, but these were never properly
implemented, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Bengal tigers are experiencing a major threat due to
habitat loss, rise of salinity and human interference inside the
area, according to the paper presented by the research team.
</P>
<P>
About 35,000 people work in the Sundarbans with a total area of
5,800 square kilometers every year for various purposes like
collection of shrimp fry, fishing and felling, the paper observed.
</P>
<P>
The Bengal tiger was once found in all the forests of
Bangladesh but today it is found only in the Sundarbans.
</P>
<P>
However, tidal ecosystem of the Sundarbans is not a suitable
habitat for the tigers, but they were forced to take shelter in
this habitat due to human disturbances and loss of other types of
forest lands, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: What Prompts Peso to Keep on Soaring? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso has kept on
soaring steadily in the past two weeks, enabling the central bank
to cut key overnight rates Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The peso averaged at a new nine-month high of 37.811 to the
U.S. dollar Tuesday, the highest since last April when it stood at
37.817. In the previous day, the peso closed at 37.830.
</P>
<P>
The peso has gained its strength since this year's first
trading day on January 4, when it ended at a seven-month high. It
closed at 38.57 pesos to the dollar, the highest since hitting
38.47 on May 27 last year.
</P>
<P>
Following the peso's continuous rise, the central bank Tuesday
lowered its overnight borrowing rate to 13 percent from 13.375
percent, and its overnight lending rate to 15 percent from 15.375
percent.
</P>
<P>
But currency traders said that the central bank move is
unlikely to invite a new wave of speculative attacks against the
peso.
</P>
<P>
What has prompted the Philippine currency to keep on rising?
</P>
<P>
The soaring peso, just like other Southeast Asian currencies,
mirrored gains of the euro and the Japanese yen against the dollar
since the beginning of the new year, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
A buying spree in favor of the euro against the dollar helped
fuel a rally in the peso and other regional currencies, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
The euro's pressure on the dollar and the increase in
investment repatriation by Japanese investors have forced the
dollar to tumble to a 27-month low against the yen this week.
</P>
<P>
The two factors supported the yen's strengthen against the
dollar. The dollar has breached the 110-yen level this week and
slipped to 108 yen Tuesday before it rebounded to 112 after the
Central Bank of Japan intervened in the market.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the yen's surge against the dollar also fueled the
gains in the peso and other Southeast Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
However, Philippine officials have attributed the peso's quick
rebound to the return of investor confidence in the Philippine
economy and a successful bond offering in the international
capital market.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said Tuesday that foreign
investors are already making distinctions among economies in the
region and are now looking at the Philippines different from the
other countries in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The success of the recent floating of 1 billion dollars of
global bonds also led to renewed confidence in the Philippine
market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government's offering of 750 million dollars of
global bonds in the U.S. market drew subscriptions totaling 2.5
billion dollars, three times more than the package. The government
described the bond floating as a success.
</P>
<P>
Other officials said that the stable demand of the dollar has
also prompted the peso to rise, as an increase in dollar demand
usually pushes down the peso-dollar rate.
</P>
<P>
There are not so much demand for dollar in the Philippines
because most corporate dollar exposures have already been served,
they said.
</P>
<P>
But a stronger peso is not always a good thing. Philippine
President Joseph Estrada said last week that the peso should be
settled at 39-40 to the dollar this year, as a stronger peso will
affect the country's exports, which already slowed down from an
average growth of 17 percent in the first 10 months of 1998 to 12
percent last November.
</P>
<P>
However, the return of investor confidence and the expected
economic recovery in 1999 may push the peso to the 35 level
against the dollar in the months ahead, traders said.
</P>
<P>
In order to keep the peso stable, they said, the central bank
could intervene if the currency continues to appreciate further in
the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said that Tuesday's key rate cuts could ease the
peso's pressure to continue soaring and further cuts in interest
rates are expected soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Initiates U.N. Talks on New Iraqi Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- France, one of the
permanent members of the United Nations Security Council, on
Tuesday initiated U.N. talks on a new policy towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In a closed meeting with U.N. ambassadors from the other four
permanent members of the council -- China, Russia, the United
States and Britain -- French Ambassador Alain Dejammet proposed
to loosen U.N. sanctions against Iraq and ease up the arms
inspection regime.
</P>
<P>
France is expected to release a general proposal on Wednesday
to reiterate its earlier ideas on the Iraqi issue, according to
U.N. diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats said the United States and Britain, which
support a tough position on Saddam Hussein's regime, have
cold-shouldered the French proposal.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador Peter Burleigh said before the meeting, "Any
change in the sanctions regime that says that Iraq has met its
disarmament requirements is unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Burleigh said work must be done to verify whether Iraq had
"relaunched" any project to produce weapons of mass destruction,
particularly in the biological field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
