<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria's Crime Rate in 1998 Hits Seven Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria registered a total
159,317 criminal offenses in 1998, record low in seven years, the
Bulgarian Interior Ministry said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Zahari Zarkov, head of Coordination and Information Analyses
at the Interior Ministry, said the figure represented a 30
percent drop from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
However, Zarkov said, the number of crimes related to drug
manufacturing and trafficking were on the rise and the trend was
likely to persist into this year.
</P>
<P>
Juvenile delinquency was on the decline whereas the number of
teenage criminals was up, which, Zarkov said, indicated a growing
trend for gang organization in these crimes.
</P>
<P>
Most of the recorded crime involved thefts, including 28,096
house-breakings, Zarkov said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that the 53.42 percent of the crimes had
been cleared, ranking Bulgaria second in Europe in terms of the
clear-up rate, said Chavdar Kroumov, head of Interior Ministry's
press office.
</P>
<P>
A large number of offenses were committed by the same persons,
usually those who were facing prosecution, Zarkov commented. Many
crimes committed around the Christmas holidays were committed by
prisoners on leave.
</P>
<P>
Last year saw a total of 7,238 cars stolen in Bulgaria --
4,297 were found and returned to their owners, Zarkov said.
</P>
<P>
Police statistics showed that the cars that most frequently
fell prey to theft were Ladas (20 percent), VWs (15 percent) and
Mercedes (13 percent). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
