<HEADLINE> Myanmar Writers Urged to Prevent Cultural Infiltration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Lieutenant
General Khin Nyunt has urged writers in the country to use
literature to prevent infiltration into the cultural field by
neo-colonialists.
</P>
<P>
Khin Nyunt, first secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and
Development Council, said Tuesday that the source of strength to
prevent the danger of neo-colonialists, who attempt to monopolize
the international media, is the way to broaden the horizons of the
people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a private literary and scholarship awards
presentation ceremony here, he said that "the base of thoughts and
knowledge is literature dealing with knowledge and catering to
aesthetic enjoyment."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the need to build up the strength of
nationalistic spirit with broad thought, outlook and knowledge of
the cultural field.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that literature played a key role in independence
and anti-colonialist struggle in the past, stressing the need also
to uplift the status of literature at a time when new pages of the
history are being opened up in building the nation and laying
foundation.
</P>
<P>
He called on contemporary writers to make efforts to present
Myanmar literature of high standards from Asia up to international
level.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, a total of 72 Pakokku U Ohn Pe Literary Awards have
been presented since 1993. U Ohn Pe is a noted Myanmar writer of
Pakokku native in northwestern Magway division.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the literary awards, the Myanmar government also
presents the National Literary Awards and Sabei Beikman
(Literature House) Manuscript Awards every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
