<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, January 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS -- The consumer prices in France in December 1998 rose
by 0.3 percent as compared with the same month in 1997, scoring
the lowest year-on-year inflation rate since December 1953.
</P>
<P>
The official economic statistics bureau INSEE said on Tuesday
that prices rose by 0.1 percent in December over November.
(France-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukrainian Supreme Soviet Chairman Alexandr Tkachenko
outlined his ideas for changes in the government's economic
reform policies to halt the decline in the country's economic
base.
</P>
<P>
Tkachenko told a meeting of leaders of the Ukrainian state
soviets that the current reform policy needed a complete
overhaul. (Ukraine-Reform)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian banks have found that the arrival of the
single currency euro has actually brought them loss from the
exchange commission between the Italian lire and other Euroland's
currencies.
</P>
<P>
According to the Italian banker's association ABI, before
January 1 their commission on money-changing was incorporated
into the difference between the buying and selling rates. But
now they are bound to buy and sell at the same rate and so the
hidden costs are completely visible. (Italy-Euro)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- At least 39,800 hectares of plantations in
Indonesia were looted in 1998, causing an estimated material loss
of 196 billion rupiah (26 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Most of the looted plantations are oil palm and rubber
plantations, the majority located in North Sumatera and East
Java," Director General of the Ministry of Forestry and
Plantations Agus Pakpahan said. (Indonesia-Plantations-Looting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Bank Indonesia has announced several new banking
laws, designed to limit foreign exchange and lending risks, and
to improve transparency, the Jakarta Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia director Subarjo Joyosumarto said the central
bank had lowered banks' maximum net open foreign exchange to 20
percent of capital, from the previous 25 percent, to reduce the
risks of exposure on foreign exchange. (Indonesia-Banking
Regulation) 
</P>
