<HEADLINE> Thailand to Help Probe Sri Lankan Rebels Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan has assured Sri Lanka that Thailand will fully cooperate
in probing Tamil rebels activities in its territory, the official
Daily News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will never allow the use of its territory by foreign
anti-government movements to attack another government, said
Pitsuwan while meeting with Sri Lanka's new Ambassador to Thailand
Karunatilaka Amunugama Monday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said Thailand is ready to cooperate with
Sri Lanka in any way and will offer full cooperation to put an end
to any speculation about rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) using Thai territory.
</P>
<P>
In a BBC World Service Radio "Asia Today" interview aired
Tuesday, Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar said,
"Some Thai ports have been used by known LTTE ships and coastal
towns on the Thai border have been used as naval bases."
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar, however, assured that relations with the Thai
government would not be soured.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that both the Thai Foreign Ministry and
the Thai army have denied that Tamil Tigers had used Thailand's
coastal areas as secret bases to ship weapons and ammunition to
northern Sri Lanka. 
</P>
