<HEADLINE> Wreckage of U.N. Plane Found in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The rebel National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) told the
United Nations that it had located the wreckage of a
U.N.-chartered cargo plane that crashed on January 2 with nine
people aboard, U.N. officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that UNITA had been asked to take a U.N.
search team to the crash site.
</P>
<P>
Initial reports, presented to Benon Sevan who is the U.N.
under-secretary in charge of security, said that there were no
survivors aboard. But the officials cautioned they had no
independent confirmation.
</P>
<P>
Sevan is returning from Angola and is expected to be back in
New York on Wednesday, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The January 2 crash was the second U.N. aircraft that had been
shot down in Angola's central highlands province of Huambo since
December 26.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, the U.N. Security Council unanimously
condemned the shoot-down of two U.N.-chartered planes over the
UNITA-held territory and blamed rebel leader Jonas Savimbi for fai
ling to cooperate with the U.N. search and rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. search team last Friday paid a brief visit to the first
crash site, some 30 kilometers east of Huambo, capital of Huambo
Province, where they found charred wreckage but were unable to con
duct an investigation simply because of the on-going fierce
fighting in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Government and UNITA blamed each other for the
clashes of the two U.N. planes, which had been delivering
humanitarian aid to the government-controlled area.
</P>
<P>
The two sides were locked in a civil war in early December,
leading to the breakdown of a 1994 U.N.-brokered peace accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
