<HEADLINE> Forest Fires Threaten Vietnam's Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Forest fires threatened Vietnam's
environment, Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A fire lasting from January 4 to January 11 ruined more than
400 hectares of protective forest and natural forest in Vietnam's
northern mountainous province of Bac Kan.
</P>
<P>
The fire broke out in Nhu Co Commune on January 4 and spread
out to Thanh Binh, Nong Ha, Nong Thinh, Binh Van, Cao Ky and Thanh
Van communes and was eventually extinguished on January 11.
</P>
<P>
According to VNA, some 72 forest fires occurred in Vietnam's
central highlands province of Kon Tum in the 1997-1998 dry season,
destroying nearly 700 hectares of forest in comparison with only 7
forest fires which devastated 45.75 hectares in the 1996-1997 dry
season.
</P>
<P>
The township of Kon Tum alone had 26 forest fires which ruined
175.5 hectares of upstream protective forest.
</P>
<P>
As many as 1,681 forest fires, said VNA, occurred nationwide
during the 1997-1998 dry season, ruining 19,819 hectares of
forest, including 6,293 hectares of natural forest, 7,888 hectares
of planted forest and 496 hectares of bamboo.
</P>
<P>
Prolonged droughts, inefficient fire fighting forces, lack of
fire extinguishers and loose coordination between local
authorities and forest rangers are attributed to forest fires, VNA
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
