<HEADLINE> Vietnam Records 12.1 Pct Industrial Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's industrial growth rate
reached 12.1 percent in 1998, Vietnam's English daily Vietnam News
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The output of state-owned enterprises represented 46.18 percent
of the country's industrial production, up by 7.93 percent
compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign-invested sector, including 35 enterprises brought
into operation in 1998, made up 31.82 percent of the nation's
industrial production, an increase of 23.33 percent compared with
1997, the highest rate recorded last year.
</P>
<P>
Non-state enterprises accounted for the remaining 22 percent,
an increase of 6.7 percent, the lowest industrial growth rate in
the sector.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam News quoted Industry Minister Dang Vu Chu as saying
that the production of major industrial products including crude
oil, cement, beer, paper, electricity and motorbikes increased
significantly and contributed to industrial growth in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector scored such achievements because of new
government policies and initiatives which created favorable
conditions for and facilitated industrial development, Chu said at
a year-end meeting in Ho Chi Minh City Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Vietnam's industrial sector attained a 5,800-6,000
million U.S. dollars export turnover. Major industrial exports
were textiles and garments, crude oil, footwear, electronic
products and coal.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's industrial sector's imports made up 6,200 million
dollars of the country's estimated import turnover of 11,350
million dollars. Major imports were machinery and industrial
production equipment.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Industry Ministry is targeting a 1999 industrial
production growth rate of 10.57 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
