<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ISRO Satellites, Launchers to Be Ariane Compatible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Space Research
Organization (ISRO) has decided to make its future satellites and
launchers compatible with Ariane space systems to enable one
organization to launch the other's satellites in orbit, official
sources said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision followed an agreement between ISRO and Ariane, the
European consortium, late last year which allows Ariane to launch
its low earth orbiting satellites aboard ISRO's medium-range Polar
Satellite Launch Vehicle (PSLV). ISRO is hopeful of bagging
satellite launching as well as satellite business from Ariane.
</P>
<P>
The Ariane-compatible mating system will be installed in its
Geostationary Satellite Launch Vehicle (GSLV), ISRO's most
ambitious rocket project expected to take off by the end of 1999.
Similarly, the Insat-3 series of satellites, too, will have Ariane
connectivity.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, ISRO designed its satellites to suit the launching
contractor. Most of its satellites have U.S. Delta compatibility,
as they were originally built to Ford Aerospace design.
</P>
<P>
Ariane maintains a full order book and, following the
ISRO-Ariane deal, there is a strong possibility of the latter
passing on some of its business to ISRO. Also, Ariane
compatibility will give ISRO the strength to bid independently for
launch and satellite building contracts, the sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0293 </DOCNO>
