<HEADLINE> Vietnam Urges Leniency for 18 Fishermen Jailed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has asked Thailand to
reduce the jail terms for 18 Vietnamese fishermen who were caught
in Thai waters last year, the Bangkok Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese were initially sentenced to one month jail and
fined 50,000 baht (1,389 U.S. dollars) each. But none could pay
the fine and opted to serve 714 days in jail instead, the Bangkok
Post quoted foreign ministry officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most of the fishermen have served about half of their jail
terms in Surat Thani, southern Thailand. And a member of the group
has died.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Thailand has expressed regret for not informing
the Vietnamese side of the death until recently.
</P>
<P>
The Thai authorities are looking into the Vietnamese request
since there is no extradition agreement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"We will consider the conditions that will enable us to meet
the Vietnamese request," one official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Currently, two Thai fishermen and a fishing trawler are
detained in Vietnam, a much smaller number than before because of
positive developments in bilateral relations after a decade of
dispute over fishing rights in overlapping territorial waters in
the Gulf of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have tried to improve their ties with an
agreement to delimit the overlapping boundary in the Gulf of
Thailand, signed in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
In March this year, commanders-in-chief of the Thai and
Vietnamese navies will sign a memorandum of understanding on joint
patrols along the 80-nautical-mile demarcation line of the
exclusive economic zone and the continental shelf between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will launch joint patrols in sea rescues and
operations against smugglers and pirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
