<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economy to Recover in 2000: Think-Tank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's leading private
economic think-tank Econit has predicted that the country's
economy will recover next year, the Indonesian Observer reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia's economy will still see a contraction of minus four
percent in 1999... (and) enter a phase of economic recovery in
2000. But this largely depends on a new platform of political
stability," Econit said in its report entitled "Econit economic
outlook 1999: The year of resolution".
</P>
<P>
The government, in its draft budget last week, forecast zero
economic growth in the 1999/2000 fiscal year compared with a
12-percent contraction expected in the 1998/99 fiscal year ending
March 31.
</P>
<P>
The report forecast an inflation rate this year of around 25
percent, higher than the government's estimate.
</P>
<P>
"The cause of (1999) inflation will be a lack of supply of food
such as rice, meat, chicken and soybeans. In addition, inflation
will also be caused by plans to end the subsidies on petrol,
electricity and rising prices of a number of commodities. With an
estimate of a budget deficit of 7.2 percent of GDP (gross domestic
product), inflation is expected to reach 25 percent in 1999," the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The draft budget assumed an average inflation of 17 percent in
1999/2000, with a budget deficit of around 4.8 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Econit said a credible leader is essential for economic
recovery in the world's fourth most populous country of 200
million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
