<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Judge to Attend Pinochet Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Baltasar Garzon, the Spanish
judge whose warrant led to the arrest of Augusto Pinochet, will
go to London to attend hearings of Britain's highest court on the
fate of the former Chilean dictator, legal sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Garzon was authorized by the General Council of Legal Powers,
the highest body governing Spanish judges, to be present when
seven Law Lords re-hear arguments next Monday on whether Pinochet
enjoys immunity from prosecution as a former head of state.
</P>
<P>
However, Garzon will take no part in the hearing which begins
on January 18. His views will be represented by the British
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
Garzon's request for Pinochet's arrest and extradition on
charges of genocide, torture and terrorism led to the dictator's
detention in London last October. Pinochet remains under police
guard at a mansion some 30 kilometers west of London.
</P>
<P>
An initial decision by the House of Lords that Pinochet had no
sovereign immunity for crimes committed during his 17-year rule
was overturned after one of the judges was found to have links to
the human rights group Amnesty International which had lobbied
for his prosecution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
