<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nobel Prize Laureate Recommends Mexico Adopt US Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Nobel Economy Prize
laureate Gary Becker has suggested Mexico adopt the US dollar to
avoid recurrent financial crises due to the peso's periodic
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Becker said that Mexico's monetary system should be perm
anently reformed through a monetary council similar to those set
up by countries like Argentina to avoid exchange rate crises such
as the 1994 currency collapse.
</P>
<P>
Becker, 68, one of the world's most influential economists,
was awarded the Nobel Prize in 1992 for his work linking economic
analysis to the sociological study of human relations and
behavior.
</P>
<P>
He said that even if monetary policy was stabilized without
permanently aligning the peso at a fixed rate to the dollar,
Mexico would continue to be affected by world financial
turbulence.
</P>
<P>
Becker recommended continuing with economic openness reforms,
boosting deregulation and privatization, and promoting free
enterprise to continue attracting foreign investment and capital
to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Last year's instability on the exchange markets with the world
financial crisis led to adjustments in interest rates and a
strong rise in inflation to a staggering 18.6 percent, a 55
percent increase above the predicted 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Wobbling exchange rates prompted a debate in financial sectors
which recommended linking the peso to the dollar through a
monetary council or through the adoption of a single currency
within the North American Free Trade market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Needs To Restructure Auto Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- As mergers sweep through the
world's auto industry, creating monolithic giants capable of
dominating the market, China's own fledgling car manufacturers
see a growing need to pull the companies together to have an even
chance of competing.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiaoyu, deputy director of the State Administration of
Machinery Industry (SAMI), acknowledged recently that China's
auto companies are still too weak and dispersed.
</P>
<P>
Now, he revealed, the administration has drawn up a plan to
accelerate the integration of the country's auto industry by
developing three huge companies and a dozen major manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Shao Qihui, the director of SAMI, believes
that if China is finally allowed into the World Trade Organiz
ation (WTO), it will have only a few years to upgrade its auto
industry to tackle the competition from international rivals.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative that we concentrate resources to develop our
own cars in the near future," he added.
</P>
<P>
There are now 200 auto companies in China but their annual
output is only 1.6 million vehicles, equal to that of a medium
sized auto factory in the west. The three largest, the Shanghai
Automotive Industry Corporation, First Automobile Works (FAW)
Group and Dongfeng Motor Corporation, each has a production
capacity of less than 200,000 vehicles per year. And FAW's annual
sales revenue is equal to only two percent of that achieved by
General Motors of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Despite stringent efforts to use domestic made parts for
foreign cars manufactured in China, more than 75 percent of the
technologies used to make new models are imported. And the time
cycle for developing a new car is at least twice that of foreign
companies.
</P>
<P>
With several large Japanese auto firms on the verge of being
taken over by larger companies, a Chinese auto industry expert
said that if the country relaxed protection of its national auto
industry, local companies, which are less competitive than the
Japanese, will be no match for the foreign giants.
</P>
<P>
He estimates that the cost of developing a new car is at least
150 million US dollars. However, the Chinese Government plans to
invest 109.1 billion yuan (1.3 billion US dollars) in the auto
industry in the last five years of the century. But, he noted, if
China wanted to develop a new car every six months, it would only
have 130 million US dollars of government funds for each one.
</P>
<P>
All auto companies in China are under government control and
are burdened with an average debt-to-asset ratio of 80 percent,
while a fierce price war is also eating into their profit margins.
</P>
<P>
"No individual auto car maker in China can currently afford
the cost of developing a new vehicle," China Qingqi Group
Vice-President Zhou Zhongwei said.
</P>
<P>
He suggests that besides the need to localize the industry,
the Chinese Government should ask foreign companies setting up
joint-ventures in China to meet certain criteria for joint
research and development activities and for technology transfer.
</P>
<P>
"We should trade our market potential for technology which we
can use in the future to develop a domestic industry," he said.
</P>
<P>
Major Chinese auto companies have sent hundreds of talented
engineers to foreign car makers to take part in research and
development projects to learn new technologies and skills which
can be used in China.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
