<HEADLINE> Stable Steel Market in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China's steel market expects
better results in 1999 with a rise in demand and a reasonable
pick-up in prices, according to China Metallurgical News.
</P>
<P>
Forecasts indicate that steel consumption will grow by about
four percent this year, alleviating the excessive oversupply,
while 1998's consumption is estimated at 110 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The higher consumption will be triggered by fixed-asset
investment although the demand for household manufactured goods
may decline.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected that steel exports will continue to drop
due to the ongoing effect of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The supply of steel resources expects to increase at a rate no
more than five percent and although a hike in prices could
improve the recovery, no substantial price rise is expected since
it will remain a buyer's market. 
</P>
