<HEADLINE> OSCE Head: Yugoslav Captives to be Soon Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The head of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe, Norwegian Foreign
Minister Knut Vollebaek, said Tuesday that the eight Yugoslav
soldiers taken captive by the ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo
would soon be released.
</P>
<P>
In Pristina, the provincial capital of Kosovo, Vollebaek said
negotiations to free the hostages ended successfully, the
Yugoslav Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We have had positive results," he said. "We have reached an
agreement with the KLA on an early release of the detainees."
</P>
<P>
However, he made no mention of the specific time for the
release of the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
International monitors in Kosovo have been talking with both
the KLA rebels and Serbian authorities since the soldiers were
kidnapped last Friday in KLA-held territory in northern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before Vollebaek's announcement, the Yugoslav army
warned the soldiers must be released "unconditionally" or it
would use force to free them.
</P>
<P>
Milivoje Novkovic, information director of the Headquarters of
the General Staff, said the captives were members of the
legitimate armed forces of the Yugoslav Federation, an
independent and sovereign state. No one had the right to deprive
them of their freedom without authorization.
</P>
<P>
"The kidnapping of Yugoslav army members by Albanian
separatists and terrorists is a flagrant example of an insane
criminal act," he said.
</P>
<P>
Novkovic welcomed the international community's condemnation
of the terrorist activities by the ethnic Albanian separatists,
and the efforts made by Vollebaek and the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) verification mission
for their release.
</P>
<P>
Novkovic said the Yugoslav military was doing everything
necessary to free the soldiers. He warned that the Yugoslav
military did not rule out the possibility of using their right to
rescue the hostages by force.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic told Vollebaek in
Belgrade on Monday that time was running out for the KLA rebels
to free the captives.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav army tanks were deployed close to Stari Trg, near
where the soldiers were being held in the village of Bajgora,
poised for action in case talks failed.
</P>
<P>
Since the outbreak of the Kosovo conflict last February, more
than 1,000 people have been killed, and tens of thousands
displaced despite the ceasefire under the peace deal struck by
Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke last October.
</P>
<P>
The Pristina Information Center said Tuesday that in the first
11 days of 1999, the armed ethnic Albanian forces in Kosovo
launched a total of 80 attacks against policemen, military troops
and civilians alike, killing four policemen and six civilians.
</P>
<P>
Nine policemen and five civilians were wounded in the attacks
while eight Yugoslav soldiers and one civilian were taken
hostage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
