<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Banks Suffer from Launch of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Italian banks have found that the
arrival of the single currency euro has actually brought them
loss from the exchange commission between the Italian lire and
other Euroland's currencies.
</P>
<P>
According to the Italian banker's association ABI, before
January 1 their commission on money-changing was incorporated
into the difference between the buying and selling rates. But
now they are bound to buy and sell at the same rate and so the
hidden costs are completely visible.
</P>
<P>
A rapid survey of exchange rates showed that a million lire
last month bought 1,005 marks or 3,335 francs. On Monday it
yielded 974 marks or 3,269 francs, resulting in loss of 30,000
and 25,000 lire respectively.
</P>
<P>
Since the introduction of the euro for non-cash transactions,
Italian banks had adopted a standing charge of 5,000 lire plus 3
percent on the overall amount being exchanged. But ABI pointed
out that the 3 percent commission charge had been fixed as a
maximum recommended rate and that, hopefully, competition between
banks would bring the percentage down.
</P>
<P>
The association also stressed that the partial arrival of a
single currency had not reduced in any way the cost storing,
transporting and insuring foreign currencies like marks and
francs. The Italian banks will lose profits from
forthcoming-lower commission, the ABI forecast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Female Students Outnumber Males in Arts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China's university
administrators are faced with something of a thorny problem they
could never have imagined in the past as the number of female
students taking arts subjects has now far overtaken the male
input.
</P>
<P>
In a survey among all students reaching minimum entry
standards for Beijing colleges, female candidates accounted for
74 percent of the total and even in subjects normally dominated
by males, the female candidates reached 42 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
And at the Shanghai International Studies University last year
the admissions department found that all eighteen of the
candidates in Beijing for arts subjects were female.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing Foreign Studies University, female students account
for 75 percent of the total. Among 1998's 62 newly recruited
students in the foreign languages department of the People's
University, only twenty are males.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics in the 1998 national college
entrance examination the ratio of male participants to female was
1:0.7, but a snap survey revealed that female examinees scored
higher in arts subjects than their male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Now in order to restore the balance, a number of colleges say
they will introduce different acceptance standards for male and
female candidates.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhou Xiaozheng, professor of sociology in the
People's University says there is no need to worry about the
situation which is very normal given the nature of China's
current development.
</P>
<P>
"The national college entrance examination is a very fair
system of choosing talented students in China. Everyone, without
regard to his or her ethnic group, gender or background, has the
right to take part in the exam. The success of female students in
the national college examination is due to their own efforts," he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
