<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Pledges Greater Commitment to Fight Against Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government has
announced a series of measures to crackdown on serious crime
after a wave of killings shocked the country in the New Year.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema, Interior Minister Rosa Russo
Jervolino and local authorities held an anti-crime meeting in
Milan Tuesday, following a rash of unrelated homicides and other
crimes there, including nine murders in the first nine days of
1999. Those crimes have shocked the country with the media and
political spotlight on what is perceived as a law-and-order
emergency.
</P>
<P>
The immediate measures announced by D'Alema at the meeting
involved more police, greater powers and more up-to-date
equipment. He also introduced a single emergency number for all
the police operation rooms in order to resume control at a local
level where small-scale crime tends to go relatively unchecked.
</P>
<P>
To achieve closer integration in the battle against crime, the
prime minister said mayors of local governments would join the
local security and public order committees chaired by the
prefects, the government's administrative and judicial
representatives.
</P>
<P>
The mayor, an elected official, has no right to become
involved in security and public order affairs under the Italian
Constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
