<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Residents Warned About Unhealthy Life Styles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Chronic illnesses such as
heart attacks, cardiovascular diseases and cancer are now
responsible for more than 75 percent of deaths in Shanghai,
China's most populous city, and the increasingly unhealthy
life-style of its residents is the main culprit.
</P>
<P>
Smoking, alcohol abuse and an excessive intake of salt are
ranked as the habits most damaging to health while infectious
diseases, once the biggest killers in this east China
municipality, are better controlled, thanks to modern medicines.
</P>
<P>
According to health statistics, only 341 people out of every
100,000 people are currently affected by such diseases, the
lowest level in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
Health experts have now warned residents in Shanghai to keep a
check on other high risk habits such as eating fat-rich food and
shunning physical exercise.
</P>
<P>
Now, in a bid to improve public awareness of health,
authorities in the municipality's education and health
departments are to promote a "health education week" which begins
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The plan, say officials, is to offer health education to
citizens thus giving them the chance of enjoying healthy
lifestyles in the new century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
