<HEADLINE> CAF Wants Fewer African World Cup Bids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The fewer African
countries to bid for 2006 World Cup, the better chances they are
likely to get, said the Confederation of African Football (CAF)
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Ghana, Morocco, Nigeria and South Africa have all
entered the race to stage the soccer showpiece which also
involves former hosts Brazil, England and Germany.
</P>
<P>
The executive committee of CAF would meet in South Africa on
January 26 to discuss with representatives from the five
candidates in an effort to trim the continent's bids,
secretary-general Mustapha Fahmy said.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that CAF cannot impose the decision that there
should be one African bid since only national associations, not
confederations, have the right to apply.
</P>
<P>
Fahmy would not disclose whether CAF favoured one country but
South Africa, which is understood to be backed by FIFA president
Sepp Blatter, is widely considered the front-runners. 
</P>
