<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly 40,000 Hectares of Plantations Looted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- At least 39,800 hectares of
plantations in Indonesia were looted in 1998, causing an estimated
material loss of 196 billion rupiah (26 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Most of the looted plantations are oil palm and rubber
plantations, the majority located in North Sumatera and East
Java," Director General of the Ministry of Forestry and
Plantations Agus Pakpahan said.
</P>
<P>
Looters hit hundreds of thousands of metric tons of oil palm
fruit, latex, cocoa beans and other items as well as destroying
plantation facilities such as vehicles, processing plants and even
employees' houses, Agus was quoted by the Jakarta Post Wednesday
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The plantation security personnel were usually outnumbered by
the looters, he said.
</P>
<P>
Agus added that a big plantation company in North Sumatera had
to deal with an average of between 30 and 50 cases of looting per
month in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The government will solve these problems and will continue to
improve the security of plantation firms," he added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is facing the worst economic crisis in its history.
The number of the poor has soared, and cases of rampant theft and
looting have also increased greatly in certain pockets of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The looters, mostly people from villages neighboring the
affected plantations, plundered the plantations because they
consider that the firms have contributed nothing to the
improvement of local welfare, Agus said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
