<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Announces New Banking Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia has announced
several new banking laws, designed to limit foreign exchange and
lending risks, and to improve transparency, the Jakarta Post
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia director Subarjo Joyosumarto said the central
bank had lowered banks' maximum net open foreign exchange to 20
percent of capital, from the previous 25 percent, to reduce the
risks of exposure on foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
"The changes in the net open position condition are intended to
encourage banks to be more careful when taking foreign exchange
position as an anticipation on possible future losses due to
exchange rate fluctuation," Subarjo told reporters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The net open position is the difference between a bank's long-
and short-term foreign exchange position.
</P>
<P>
Subarjo said that the new ruling was signed by Bank Indonesia
Governor Sjahril Sabirin on December 31, 1998 and was effective
since the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Banks breaching the new ruling would face stiffer sanctions
according to the new 1998 Banking Law, he said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank had also introduced a ruling on the legal
lending limit of banks.
</P>
<P>
The lending limit to a non-affiliated single party had been
relaxed to 30 percent of capital, from the former maximum of 20
percent, for the period until December 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
The lending limit would be tightened to 25 percent from January
1, 2002 until December 31, 2002, Subarjo said, adding that the
limit would be returned to the 20-percent level beginning 2003.
</P>
<P>
Subarjo said certain lending activities, however, were allowed
to surpass the 30-percent limitation.
</P>
<P>
This included extending heavily-subsidized government loans in
which the bank is the executor, and lending to open letters of
credit.
</P>
<P>
He added that funds for buying Bank Indonesia promissory notes
and government-guaranteed bonds were excluded from any of the new
lending limits.
</P>
<P>
Subarjo dismissed worries that the new 30-percent lending limit
requirement could be abused by bank owners to recapitalize their
ailing banks, saying the central bank's supervision system had
greatly improved.
</P>
<P>
According to the new 1998 Bank Law, banks are now obliged to
issue financial reports every quarter, compared with twice a year
under the previous laws. The new reporting schedule, which will
start in June, must include records of lending and capital status.
</P>
<P>
Subarjo said that under this new law, banking secrecy only
covers the liability side, not the asset side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ocalan Risks Trial if He Remains in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan risks being tried in Italy if he remains in the country,
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"If Ocalan remains in Italy, he risks being put on trial
here," D'Alema told the Senate, adding that if Ocalan decides to
go, he can do so because he is a free man.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly, if he were to leave the country, he would get us
out of some difficulties," the premier said, pointing out that
the government has always sought to have Ocalan tried for the
crimes he is accused of, even though they were not committed in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish extradition request accused Ocalan of a long list
of terrorism and terrorism-related crimes. His extradition is
ruled out by Italian law, which excludes it to countries where
the death sentence is in force.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema said that, while arguing that he should be tried, the
Italian government has never seen the case as a "simple judicial
fact" and the accusations are to be considered within the context
of the Kurdish people's rights.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema said both the possibility of granting political asylum
and simple expulsion were ruled out. He explained that the
expulsion would be impracticable and the political asylum would
have violated the Geneva Convention, which does not envisage
political asylum for those accused of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was arrested in Rome on November 12 last year, and the
Rome Appeals Court lifted on December 16 travel restrictions on
him. On December 23, D'Alema announced that he could leave Italy,
ignoring the extradition request by the Turkish government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
