<HEADLINE> "Fledgling Eagles" Drive Helps Young Grow Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A drive to prepare Chinese
young people for the demands of the 21st century is progressing
well, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quotes Sun Shoushan,
vice-director of the National Work Committee on Young Pioneers as
saying that the Trans-Century Fledgling Eagles drive, which began
in 1994, was designed to help provide skills to youngsters that
will allow them to survive and develop in a competitive world.
</P>
<P>
The drive's mission is to help participants develop a "healthy
and active mentality."
</P>
<P>
Sun said a healthy and active mentality includes a strong
consciousness of patriotism, self-discipline, self-reliance,
team-work and creativity.
</P>
<P>
Chinese youngsters are encouraged to learn and think on their
own while nurturing a competitive attitude that aspires to
confidence, perseverance and self-discipline.
</P>
<P>
Learning to co-operate with others is crucial for youngsters'
growth. Sun said that young people should welcome a sense of
responsibility towards society and help others.
</P>
<P>
The drive seeks to inspire the nation's youth to care about
science and to be more skeptical in their studies. Creativity of
youngsters is highly sought.
</P>
<P>
In addition to trying to overcome mental obstacles to academic
excellence, the drive's organizers want to improve young people's
primary survival and development skills.
</P>
<P>
These skills involve taking care of themselves and improving
basic work skills and service skills. The program stresses the
use of creativity in applying science to practice, the paper
says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
