<HEADLINE> Probe Finds Violation of Law by Soeharto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Spokesman of Indonesia's
attorney-general's office Soehandoyo Tuesday announced temporary
results of the probe of former president Soeharto, which indicated
violations of the law by Soeharto during his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
An attorney-general team comprising 13 senior prosecutors has
indicated that criminal elements as well as corruption had taken
place in the Timor national car project, as well as in charitable
foundations chaired by Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Soehandoyo, however, refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot reveal any further details because we still need to
delve deeply to confirm their accuracy," the Indonesian Observer
Wednesday quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The attorney-general team Tuesday conducted an evaluation of
the ongoing investigation into corruption and power abuse
allegations against Soeharto, who was forced to step down on May
21 last year amid the country's worst economic and political
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the Timor national car project, the government granted
tax breaks to PT Timor Putra Nasional, owned by Soeharto's son
Hutomo 'Tommy' Mandala Putra, to import completely built-up sedans
from South Korean car maker Kia Motor. The project had caused the
country losses of 1.55 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
During his reign, Soeharto chaired nine charities, which have
been accused of receiving government privileges and facilities as
well as being one of Soeharto's main business vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto has handed over the control of seven of the nine
charitable foundations to the government.
</P>
<P>
"For more accuracy, the team will have to summon the other
parties related to these issues. We still need more information
from witnesses in order to probe the two cases clearly,"
Soehandoyo said.
</P>
<P>
He said the attorney-general's office will soon question other
treasurers of the charities, who include Soeharto's daughter Siti
'Tutut' Hardiyanti Rukmana and former minister Bustanil Arifin.
</P>
</TEXT>
