<BODY>
<HEADLINE> On-Line Rail Ticketing System Hits The Buffers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- People who use the Internet to
book rail tickets on-line merely to test the system and never
pick them up have been criticized for their behavior in a signed
article in Beijing Daily, which says they are causing problems
for railway staff.
</P>
<P>
Since the Beijing railway bureau started its on-line ticketing
service on New Year's day, approximately 350 tickets were booked
up to January 5 but only 70 tickets were collected and used,
bureau officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
A bureau official said that two staff have been deployed to
handle the administration work but because many people didn't
follow the system through, they are experiencing problems in
keeping it efficient and the records accurate.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that there are two main reasons for this
behavior: curious Internet browsers who simply want to try out
the system and potential passengers who are keen to check out if
it really works but have no intention of traveling.
</P>
<P>
The railway bureau admitted that it knew the ID card numbers
of the offenders and maybe even their E-mail addresses but didn't
want to take official action at this stage in the hope that this
warning will persuade them to stop abusing the service and behave
responsibly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
