<HEADLINE> U.S. to Offer Ukraine 195 Million Dollars in Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States Congress has
decided to grant Ukraine 195 million U.S. dollars in aid in 1999
to support the former Soviet republic's ongoing economic reforms,
U.S. ambassador to Ukraine Stephen Pifer said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But half of the amount will be made available only after
February 18, when U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
delivers a positive report to the congress on Ukraine's reform
process and U.S. investment in the country, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine must push forward large-scale economic reforms and
effectively implement new trade and tax laws so as to qualify for
the aid, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday and Tuesday, a U.S. government delegation, headed by
Albright's special aide in charge of U.S. aid to newly
independent states, was visiting Ukraine to prepare the report.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the U.S. also demanded that half of its 225 million
dollars in aid to Ukraine be linked to Ukraine's reform
achievements. 
</P>
