<HEADLINE> Salt Lake Officials Deny Games to Be Moved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Salt Lake City Olympic
organizers scrambled Monday to dismiss reports that the 2002
Winter Games might be moved.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the Games will be in Salt Lake City in 2002," said
Robert Garff, chairman of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee's
board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, senior International Olympic Committee
member Marc Hodler said the Games could be moved if the bribery
scandal erodes Salt Lake City's ability to raise funds.
</P>
<P>
Michale Payne, marketing chief for the IOC, said Hodler's
statement were not the official position of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
Payne said he could only see "war, earthquake, civil
disturance or an act of God" moving the Games.
</P>
<P>
John Krismsky, head of the joint marketing venture between
Salt Lake and the U.S. Olympic Committee, said Hodler is "simply
wrong."
</P>
<P>
Krismsky hopes to find the $250 million left from the $859
million goal by August 2000.
</P>
<P>
Governor Michael Leavitt, who has taken a lead role in the
Salt
Lake City cleanup, said: "I vigorously disagree with Hodler's
analysis." 
