<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FA Buys Wembley in 103m Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Football Association of
England has finally clinched a 103 millions pound deal to buy
Wembley stadium.
</P>
<P>
Wembley plc's board ended months of speculation by putting pen
to paper to hand over the national stadium to English football's
governing body.
</P>
<P>
News of the deal was leaked ahead of a proposed announcement
on the Stock Exchange on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The move will pave the way for the 320m project to build a new
stadium, which would form the centrepiece of the bid to host the
2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Shareholders' approval is expected within the next month to
seal the deal, which sees ownership of the stadium and adjoining
land passing to the English National Stadium Development Company
(ENSDC), a subsidiary of the FA.
</P>
<P>
ENSDC chief executive Bob Stubbs dismissed reports that delays
had been threatening to scupper the deal - but he did admit that
negotiations had been "complicated".
</P>
<P>
Other interested parties had attempted to scupper the deal.
Only last week leisure company ENIC made a last-ditch bid to
capitalise on a reported split among the Wembley plc board over
the proposals.
</P>
<P>
But the ENSDC cemented the deal and Stubbs declared: "I'm
absolutely delighted.
</P>
<P>
"A new National Stadium is crucial to the 2006 World Cup bid
and as the FA will now own the stadium, all profits will be
ploughed back into the game's grass-roots."
</P>
<P>
But there are still potential problems that must be resolved
and the new National Stadium is not likely to be opened before
the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
Rebuilding work cannot begin until consent has been obtained
from Brent council and English Heritage, and the debate over the
future of the evocative Twin Towers, which are expected to have
to be knocked down, still rages.
</P>
<P>
The FA's acting executive director David Davies said: "This is
clearly a huge boost to the 2006 campaign and it is a major
milestone in the development of a stadium for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"What we have to do now is to press on with increased vigour
to make sure that the stadium is ready for the 2003 World
Athletics Championships and then, we all hope and pray, for the
major event in 2006.
</P>
<P>
"We congratulate Ken Bates and the FA staff who have worked
long hours on this deal, as well as all those at the English
National Stadium Development Company," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
