<HEADLINE> Jordan's Move to Have NBA-wide Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan plans to
hang up his Nikes Wedneaday, a decision that would signal the end
of the Chicago Bulls' dynasty and the start of a new NBA era.
</P>
<P>
According to people with knowledge of his long-awaited decisi
on,
the transcendent star plans to make his announcement at a news
conference in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
That would bring the curtain down on an unparalleled 14-year
career of rings, recordss and worldwide recognition, and sent in
motion the rebuilding of the six-time champions and retooling of
the NBA's very image.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's departure would pave the way for Tim Floyd to
officially succeed Phil Jackson as coach and be the final straw
in the dismantling of the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
Without Jordan, the Bulls aren't expected to re-sign free
agents Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman, the core of the team
that beat Utah in the 1998 Finals.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's retirement would stamp the Reggie Miller-led Indiana
Pacers as the new leader on the Eastern Conference block. Under
first-year coach Larry Bird, the Pacers lost to the Bulls in a
seven-game conference final last spring.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's Air Apparent would not be as obvious at a time when
the NBA is looking to win back fans after s six-month labor
dispute. Asked about filling Jordan's shoes last week, Stern
said: "One of these days, Michael Jordan is going to retire. It
is sad, but inevitable. The rest of the best players in the world
are itching to get the opportunity to get onto that stage."
</P>
</TEXT>
