<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moderate Growth of AIDS in Moldova in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A total of 415 AIDS infected
and four AIDS diseases were reported in the Republic of Moldova in
1998, Chief of the National AIDS Center Stefan Gheorghita was
quoted Tuesday by the Moldovan Interlik news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
A moderate growth of this disease is observed, compared with
1997, when 407 AIDS cases were reported, Gheorghita said, adding
that as in the previous year, the infection continued
disseminating among able-bodied young people under the age of 39.
</P>
<P>
Gheorghita said that 84 percent of the total number of the
infected make up addicts, taking narcotic drugs by means of
intravenous injections and using the same needles and syringes for
groups of people.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 4,000 drug addicts have been officially registered in
the medical institutions of the country and in the police,
according to the latest statistics. But local experts estimated
that the real number is between 40,000 and 120,000 people, who day
by day become victims of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
There are 20.45 infected per 100,000 people in Moldova, with
the main AIDS infection center in Belti municipality where there
are 252.23 infected per 100,000. In the capital of the republic it
constitutes 41.30, in rural areas it wavers between 15.58 in
Falesti and 0.74 in Orhei.
</P>
<P>
The course of the implementation of the National Program for
Preventing and Combating AIDS for the period up to 2000 was
examined last year at a government sitting of the
Interinstitutional Commission for AIDS Prevention and at
collegiums of the Ministry for Health Protection, where measures
were outlined for improving the epidemic situation.
</P>
<P>
According to Gheorghita, this year the experts are planning to
improve the mechanism of epidemic supervision over the AIDS
infection, to implement a number of measures to this effect and to
carry out a whole range of actions for instructing the population
on preventing the infection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Army Helps Eliminate Power Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani army has got
into the Water and Power Development Authority (WAPDA) with the
mission to eliminate power theft and to affect recovery of the
defaulting amount.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters in Lahore Tuesday, WAPDA Chairman Zulfiqar
Ali Khan said that the operation will commence from January 15,
the Associated Press of Pakistan reported.
</P>
<P>
Zulfiqar advised the power thieves to end their evil practice
for their own good as well as in the interest of the nation. He
also exhorted the defaulters of WAPDA, particularly chronic ones,
to clear their dues forthwith to save themselves from the evil
consequences.
</P>
<P>
He warned that anyone found indulging in power theft would not
be spared and the defaulters would be dealt with strictly.
</P>
<P>
The WAPDA chief expressed his confidence in revamping WAPDA and
setting the institution in order despite its multifarious
maladies.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the army would continue this operation for
six months and after that most of the force would go back.
</P>
<P>
He placed the rate of power theft in Pakistan at around 30
percent, saying it was much higher than in the other countries.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that a staggering amount of 14 billion rupees
(304 million U.S. dollars) was outstanding against private
consumers besides 28 billion rupees (608 million dollars) due from
the government.
</P>
<P>
The army, he said, has been called upon to avert the impending
disaster, and to make WAPDA a productive organization once again.
The army will be employed at different tiers of the distribution
system for the purpose.  
</P>
