<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Automakers Form Alliance in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Nine major global automakers
formed a new trade association in the United States Tuesday to
represent the common interests of their members on policy issues,
according to a news report received here.
</P>
<P>
The companies forming the association, called the Alliance of
Automobile Manufacturers, include BMW, DaimlerChrysler, Ford,
General Motors, Mazda, Nissan, Toyota, Volkswagen and Volvo.
</P>
<P>
The Washington-based alliance said in a news release that its
members have 255 manufacturing facilities in 33 U.S. states with
642,000 employees and cover some 90 percent of U.S. vehicle sales.
</P>
<P>
It has a special commitment to improving the environment and
motor vehicle safety, said alliance chairman Peter Pestillo, who
is also vice chairman of Ford Motor Company.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the alliance came after the dissolution of the
American Automobile Manufacturers Association (AAMA) on December
31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The 98-year-old trade association, whose members were three
major U.S. automakers, closed in the wake of the merger of
Chrysler and Daimler Benz of Germany last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
