<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Plunge as Investors Take Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks plunged
Tuesday, dragged down mainly by profit-taking as investors cashed
in the buoyant market.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite suffered its first loss
since the New York stock market opened on Jan. 4 this year,
closing at 2,320.75, down 63.84. The Nasdaq was up 40.18 at a
record high of 2,384.59 Monday.
</P>
<P>
Among the biggest losers in the Nasdaq composite was
Amazon.com, which fell 17 15/16 at 166 11/12 during the trading
day. Yahoo and Intel also sank ahead of their fourth-quarter
earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average was down 145.21 at 9,474.68,
the second consecutive drop. The Dow lowered 24.43 at 9,619.89
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index also dropped 24.37 at 1,239.51,
while the NYSE composite index was down 9.45 at 594.59.
</P>
<P>
"Shares rose too far too fast in a remarkable week in the
market," said Franklin Morton, research chief at Ariel Capital
Management in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
A week into the year, the Nasdaq was up 7.3 percent, the Dow up
4.1 percent and the S&AMP;P up 2.5 percent. Investors now decided to
take profits from the flying high market.
</P>
<P>
The slump was also driven by the weaker U.S. dollar against the
Japanese yen Monday, which reduced to 108.93 yen, a 28-month low.
Investors were concerned with the lower dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
