<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Apple Browning Delayed By U.S. Agriculture Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Scientists from
Agriculture Research Center in Beltsville, Maryland, have come
up with a way to keep apples from turning brown for up to five
weeks after they have been sliced or peeled.
</P>
<P>
The new technique which uses natural products and doesn't
require special packaging, could eventually have a major impact
on the marketability of fresh-cut fruit.
</P>
<P>
Most apples, once cut, begin to turn brown in a matter of
minutes. This browning known as enzymatic oxidation, has been a
major impediment to expanding the "shelf life" and marketability
of fresh-cut fruit.
</P>
<P>
The new anti-browning treatment uses a combination of
compounds, either natural products or their derivatives, including
various combinations of enzymatic inhibitors, reducing agents and
anti-microbial compounds containing calcium.
</P>
<P>
The treatment also can slow down microbial decay and changes in
organic acids and sugars during storage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Be Flexible on EU Majority Voting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain Tuesday said it would
keep an open mind to suggestions that the European Union should
make more of its decisions by less than a unanimous vote, even
those on tax, in a departure likely to arouse domestic resentment.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Prime Minister Tony Blair said Britain had
always appreciated the need for an extension of the so-called
qualified majority voting system and in terms of tax issues, each
proposal would be judged on its merits, according to a Reuters
report.
</P>
<P>
This appeared to be a softer line than that adopted by the
government late last year when it was faced with a barrage of
European tax scare stories in the press.
</P>
<P>
Blair's spokesman was responding to remarks made earlier
Tuesday by German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer who said his
government favored killing off the need for unanimous voting in
most areas of European Union decision making.
</P>
<P>
"We have never said we opposed the extension of qualified
majority voting and in terms of tax issues we would consider each
proposal on its merits," the spokesman was quoted by Reuters as
saying. "If something is proposed (the cabinet) would clearly need
to discuss it and look at the advantages and we would need strong
convincing."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
