<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gaddafi Meets Saudi, S. African Envoys on Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Libyan leader Moammar Gaddafi
Tuesday met Saudi Arabia's Prince Bandar Ibn Sultan and an envoy
of South African President Nelson Mandela on the long-running
Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi prince, who is the kingdom's ambassador to
Washington, and Jakes Gerwel, who is director-general of Mandela's
office, were trying to persuade Gaddafi to surrender the two
Libyans suspected of bombing a Pan Am flight over Lockerbie,
Scotland in 1988.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here from Libyan capital Tripoli,
the two envoys handed over messages from Saudi King Fahd and
Mandela on "the efforts exerted by the two countries to find a
solution to the so-called Lockerbie issue."
</P>
<P>
The contents of the letters were not disclosed, but the Libyan
News Agency said a six-point new proposal on solving the Lockerbie
issue was made by King Fahd and Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans were accused by the U.S. and Britain of
planting a bomb aboard the passenger plane that exploded in the
air, killing 270 people in the plane and on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who has good relations with the Libyan leader, talked
with British Prime Minister Tony Blair during his visit to South
Africa on January 6 on the Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi envoy has reportedly close connection with
Washington. The two envoys arrived at Tripoli international
airport on a Saudi jet, which was granted a special permission to
fly into Libya by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. slapped an air-travel ban on Libya after Gaddafi
refused to surrender the two suspects on the ground that they
would never get a fair trial in either the U.S. or Britain.
</P>
<P>
A compromise was made when the U.S. and Britain decided the
suspects could be sent to the Netherlands for trial before a panel
of Scottish judges according to Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
Libya has agreed in principle to turn over the suspects, but
said arrangments should be made beforehand for their security and
if convicted, they should serve their prison terms in Libya.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has decided that the sanctions will
be suspended once the two suspects are surrendered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
