<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investors to Return to Biotech Stocks: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Investors are expected to
renew their interest in biotechnology stocks in 1999, a survey in
the United States has found.
</P>
<P>
The New York-based Genetic Engineering News (GEN), which
conducted the survey, said on Tuesday that hot biotech stock picks
for 1999 include veteran companies and those focusing on cell
growth, cell multiplication and tissue engineering.
</P>
<P>
The GEN said in its January 15 issue that investors shieded
away from biotech stocks in 1998 due to disappointing results in
several clinical trials and instability in the global markets.
</P>
<P>
They are now seeking companies with a revenue stream, strong
potential earnings and near-term product launches.
</P>
<P>
Biotechnology is seen by investors as a profit-making business
sector instead of a R&AMP;D enterprise as they saw it before, an
analysis pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. stock market had double-digit gains for the fourth
consecutive year in major indexes in 1998, led by information and
communication technology stocks with biotechnology shares left
behind.  
</P>
</TEXT>
