<HEADLINE> UK Launches Attacks on High-Rate Burglaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Home Secretary Jack
Straw unveiled burglary attack strategy on Tuesday, saying burglars
would face a minimum of three years in jail if caught over three
times.
</P>
<P>
His aim was to reduce the number of burglaries in England and
Wales, currently running at just over a million a year -- the
highest rate in the Western world.
</P>
<P>
The measure will take effect by the end of the year and mean
burglars will be sent to prison for at least three years after their
third conviction.
</P>
<P>
Straw insisted the law had now been modified to act in a "just
way" to permit particular personal circumstances to be taken into
consideration by courts.
</P>
<P>
However, both the opposition and civil rights leaders attacked
Straw's adoption of a "three strikes and you're out" strategy for
burglars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
