<HEADLINE> WTO Establishes Panel to Review EU Banana Import Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Dispute Settlement Body
(DSB) of the World Trade Organization (WTO) Tuesday agreed to set
up a panel to arbitrate within 90 days if the new banana import
policy of the European Union (EU) is in conformity with a previous
WTO ruling.
</P>
<P>
Following the WTO ruling in September 1997 that the EU's old
banana regime violated trade rules, the EU modified the policy and
implemented it on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador, together with Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico, Panama, and
the United States, complained that the modified EU policy was
still against the WTO rules.
</P>
<P>
Both the EU and Ecuador requested setting up of a panel to
settle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the DSB chairman Monday, Guatemala, Honduras,
Panama and the United States tried to block the EU's request,
arguing that the EU's request is causing confusion and it has no
legal basis for its complaint.
</P>
<P>
As a compromise, the three-man panel established Tuesday is
supposed to deal with issues raised by both the EU and Ecuador:
two topics under one panel.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the DSB special meeting Tuesday, U.S. Ambassador
Rita Hayes called on the EU to "negotiate a substantive resolution
of this dispute" but she did not rule out use of sanctions against
the EU.
</P>
<P>
"The United States, of course, retains all of its WTO rights
and may exercise those rights whenever it wishes," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
