<HEADLINE> France to Present Proposal on New Control System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- France will present on Tuesday to
four other permanent members of the United Nations Security
Council a proposal on establishing a new disarmament control
system in Iraq to replace the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry officials said that French ambassador
to the U.N. Alain Dejammet will display for the first time the
French "ideas" on the new control methods in Iraq to his
counterparts from the United States, Britain, China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador presented the proposal to U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan Tuesday morning, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said on Tuesday in
Moscow, where he was making a visit, that France would submit to
other members of the Security Council some ideas on how to go out
of the present situation and change the U.N. monitoring method in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
France has proposed establishing a new regime of disarmament
control in Iraq while lifting the oil embargo on Iraq imposed by
the U.N. eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. Secretary of State Madelaine Albright said on
Tuesday it is not time to talk about lifting embargo because Iraq
must completely disarm itself first.
</P>
<P>
She said that Washington is only interested in studying
suggestions on improving the efficiency of the UNSCOM. 
</P>
