<HEADLINE> UK Minister Says Misconducted Hospital "Shameful" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- British Health Secretary Frank
Dobson said on Tuesday an official probe into a top-security
mental hospital painted a "shameful picture."
</P>
<P>
The report, conducted by Peter Fallon on the Personality
Disorder Unit (PDU) at the Ashworth high security mental hospital
in Maghull, Merseyside, uncovered a catalogue of drug abuse,
pornography, poor patient care and security lapses.
</P>
<P>
"Too many people at Ashworth failed to do properly the jobs
they were paid to do," Dobson said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the National Health Service (NHS) to take action
against staff found to be culpable in the report.
</P>
<P>
There are three such hospitals in Britain -- Broadmoor in
Berkshire, Rampton in Nottinghamshire and Ashworth, and they are
home to some of the country's most dangerous criminals.
</P>
<P>
Dobson said: "For the foreseeable future, the three special
hospitals must continue to be the main providers of high security
services. There is no practical alternative in the short term."
</P>
<P>
Fallon, the investigator, said the situation had not been the
fault of staff. "The problem here was the system," he said. "The
system itself was rotten - it needed changing. The nurses, on the
whole, were doing an extremely good job."
</P>
<P>
He added that he found pornography was "widely available on the
ward; patients were running their own businesses; hospitals were
ignored and security was farcical."
</P>
<P>
The inquiry said the personality disorder unit was "a deeply
flawed creation."
</P>
<P>
"A number of highly serious reports have demonstrated Ashworth
Hospital's failure to care for and manage a large group of
severely personality disordered patients," Fallon said in the
report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
