<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Resumes Aid to Moldova After 18-Month Suspension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Moldova will
soon receive a 35-million-dollar tranche of the Extended Facility
Fund from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) after a suspension
of one year and a half.
</P>
<P>
The Board of Directors of the IMF decided last week to resume
its financial assistance to Moldova, the Romanian Rompres news
agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mark Horton, IMF resident representative in Chisinau, was
quoted by the Moldovan BASA-Press news agency as saying that
Moldova practically met all the conditions it had agreed with the
fund to gain further financing, the major achievement being the
adoption of the 1999 budget and new administrative-territorial
legislation.
</P>
<P>
The credit is granted to the National Bank of Moldova to
complete the country's reserves of foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
According to Mark Horton, the IMF was planning to change the
reimbursement conditions for the next tranches. In particular, to
raise the repayment period from 5-7 years to 10 years and the
grace period from 2-3 to 5 years. The fund also intended to slip
the annual interest rate from 5.5 down to 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moldova has "good chances" to enjoy agreements of this kind, as
such facilities are granted only to poor nations and those lacking
foreign financing, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of IMF financial assistance has cleared the way
for the World Bank to disburse the second tranche of its SAL-II
loan, and the 35-million-dollar loan will be used to fill in the
budgetary deficit to honor exterior obligations and pay off
salary and pensions arrears.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and the World Bank suspended their financial assistance
to Moldova in 1997 due to the "worsening political and economic
situation" of the former Soviet republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990113.0368 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diana Fund Donates 1 Million Pounds to Landmine Charities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Diana, Princess of Wales,
Memorial Fund Tuesday donated over 1 million pounds (1.6 million
U.S. dollars) of grants to 13 charities working with the victims
of landmines.
</P>
<P>
The 13 charities cover landmine projects in Africa, South
America, the Middle East, Asia and Europe. Many deal with the
rehabilitation of victims who have lost limbs.
</P>
<P>
The fund's trustees defended their decision to give cash solely
to victims of landmines and none to landmine clearance.
</P>
<P>
"Like Princess Diana we are strongly in favor of landmine
clearance, but we have to keep asking ourselves how best we can
make a difference with our money," said Christopher Spence, a
trustee of the fund which was set up after Diana's death in a car
crash in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
Spence said he would not rule out that grants would be awarded
to projects for mine clearance in the future, but they had to bear
in mind that governments had pumped millions of pounds into mine
clearance.
</P>
<P>
In the final months of her life, the princess threw herself
into campaigning for victims of landmines and pushing for a
worldwide ban. Television pictures of her visiting victims around
the world brought the issue firmly to public attention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
